When we have the question
and answer session

00:01:34.650 --> 00:01:36.860
after the main presentations,

00:01:36.860 --> 00:01:40.610
understand that if you ask a
question, you are consenting

00:01:40.610 --> 00:01:43.840
to be part of the webcast.

00:01:43.840 --> 00:01:46.580
We hope you enjoy this symposium
and the treasure display

00:01:46.580 --> 00:01:47.880
that we have after that.

00:01:47.880 --> 00:01:52.200
In a bit, I'll have Lucia
Wolfe, our specialist for Italy,

00:01:52.200 --> 00:01:54.360
come up here and
say a few words.

00:01:54.360 --> 00:01:57.400
Just please know that the
collections of the Library

00:01:57.400 --> 00:01:58.770
of Congress are for you.

00:01:58.770 --> 00:02:00.070
They're for everybody.

00:02:00.070 --> 00:02:02.530
These are open to the public.

00:02:02.530 --> 00:02:06.880
Our specialist for Italy
Lucia will tell you something

00:02:06.880 --> 00:02:08.180
about them in a bit.

00:02:08.180 --> 00:02:12.500
And I look forward to you
all seeing the exhibit,

00:02:12.500 --> 00:02:14.360
the display afterwards.

00:02:14.360 --> 00:02:16.860
So by all means, contact Lucia

00:02:16.860 --> 00:02:21.410
if you ever have questions
concerning research and Italy.

00:02:21.410 --> 00:02:25.450
But before Lucia comes
up, I have the pleasure

00:02:25.450 --> 00:02:29.080
of interesting Diana
Femia who is president

00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:33.120
of the greater Washington
DC region

00:02:33.120 --> 00:02:37.590
of the National Organization
of Italian American Women.

00:02:37.590 --> 00:02:38.890
I made it.

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:40.190
I made it.

00:02:40.190 --> 00:02:43.090
It is Diana who suggested
this event to the library.

00:02:43.090 --> 00:02:45.690
And I'm very pleased
to work with you.

00:02:45.690 --> 00:02:47.020
We both are, Lucia and I both.

00:02:47.020 --> 00:02:48.320
So thank you.

00:02:48.320 --> 00:02:52.510
So I now give the
floor to Diana.

00:02:52.510 --> 00:02:57.800
[ Applause ]

00:02:57.800 --> 00:03:01.200
&gt;&gt; Diana Femia: That's
right, you're taller than me.

00:03:01.200 --> 00:03:05.240
Well, I don't have to
introduce myself, and in order

00:03:05.240 --> 00:03:12.820
to make it easy for you,
we use NOIAW as the acronym

00:03:12.820 --> 00:03:16.680
for the National Organization.

00:03:16.680 --> 00:03:23.830
We are an organization that was
established in 1980 in New York.

00:03:23.830 --> 00:03:29.730
It was a group of women who
were looking for an organization

00:03:29.730 --> 00:03:34.180
that only Italian
American Women were.

00:03:34.180 --> 00:03:39.410
Most organizations you will
find are male organizations.

00:03:39.410 --> 00:03:41.850
And so the women just
hang on somewhere.

00:03:41.850 --> 00:03:46.490
But we are the only
one in the country

00:03:46.490 --> 00:03:50.480
that has Italian American
women, and I have to say

00:03:50.480 --> 00:03:53.500
that we have Italiophiles
in our group.

00:03:53.500 --> 00:03:55.870
They are not all
Italian Americans.

00:03:55.870 --> 00:03:57.860
They are other nationalities,

00:03:57.860 --> 00:04:02.580
one of them sitting
right here today.

00:04:02.580 --> 00:04:04.350
And the reason they decided

00:04:04.350 --> 00:04:08.810
to start this organization
is basically to unite

00:04:08.810 --> 00:04:15.340
and connect women of
Italian American background,

00:04:15.340 --> 00:04:20.380
and to promote cultural
and educational events.

00:04:20.380 --> 00:04:26.030
And this is basically
what we do.

00:04:26.030 --> 00:04:32.210
And I would say about 12 years
ago, they started indicating

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:35.380
that maybe we should
have some regions.

00:04:35.380 --> 00:04:37.010
And so we have a
region in Rhode Island

00:04:37.010 --> 00:04:39.140
and we have a region
in Connecticut.

00:04:39.140 --> 00:04:42.220
There's the metro
regions in New York.

00:04:42.220 --> 00:04:44.150
And then Washington DC.

00:04:44.150 --> 00:04:49.040
We were the first one of
the regions to come about.

00:04:49.040 --> 00:04:54.150
And I have to say, it
has been really a great

00:04:54.150 --> 00:04:55.450
learning experience.

00:04:55.450 --> 00:05:02.070
I think even for me, whose
father continued to tell her

00:05:02.070 --> 00:05:04.270
that she came from the
greatest group of people

00:05:04.270 --> 00:05:09.850
in the world, the Italians.

00:05:09.850 --> 00:05:12.810
So it's really interesting.

00:05:12.810 --> 00:05:15.590
And if you're interested
in the organization,

00:05:15.590 --> 00:05:18.700
I have some brochures here

00:05:18.700 --> 00:05:27.100
which gives you information
on what we are.

00:05:28.380 --> 00:05:31.000
Every year, at our
national luncheon,

00:05:31.000 --> 00:05:36.690
we give out about four
or five scholarships.

00:05:36.690 --> 00:05:39.030
And they are to young women,

00:05:39.030 --> 00:05:41.630
either undergraduate
or graduate students.

00:05:41.630 --> 00:05:44.980
And we also try to promote
the Italian language.

00:05:44.980 --> 00:05:50.500
So in promoting the Italian
language, we always try

00:05:50.500 --> 00:05:55.050
to give a scholarship to
a person who is majoring

00:05:55.050 --> 00:05:59.680
in Italian; Italian literature,
the Italian language.

00:05:59.680 --> 00:06:04.280
Because let's face it,
we want to promote this.

00:06:04.280 --> 00:06:14.440
And basically, we have
events, probably monthly.

00:06:14.440 --> 00:06:20.170
We try. Actually, next month on
November 7th we're having a tour

00:06:20.170 --> 00:06:26.130
of the Jefferson building
by the tour group there.

00:06:26.130 --> 00:06:30.340
And we were there about
five or six years ago

00:06:30.340 --> 00:06:34.060
and there were members who
told me this was a great tour,

00:06:34.060 --> 00:06:35.460
"Can't we do it again?"

00:06:35.460 --> 00:06:37.640
So we're doing it again.

00:06:37.640 --> 00:06:42.940
And I hope some of you will be
able to join us, because it is

00:06:42.940 --> 00:06:45.760
at 11:00 in the morning.

00:06:45.760 --> 00:06:47.730
They don't want to
do tours at night.

00:06:47.730 --> 00:06:49.330
And believe me, with
the traffic,

00:06:49.330 --> 00:06:50.880
I don't think so either.

00:06:50.880 --> 00:07:00.770
But anyway, we are also
working right now to start

00:07:00.770 --> 00:07:04.060
on our epiphany celebration
which is

00:07:04.060 --> 00:07:08.750
where we honor three
Italian American women

00:07:08.750 --> 00:07:15.250
as three wise women,
versus three wise men, okay.

00:07:15.250 --> 00:07:19.650
And we've already
actually identified three

00:07:19.650 --> 00:07:23.030
for this coming year in January.

00:07:23.030 --> 00:07:28.020
And we generally have an event.

00:07:28.020 --> 00:07:30.590
It's going to be on
January the 10th.

00:07:30.590 --> 00:07:35.480
And if you're on our mailing
list, you will see it.

00:07:35.480 --> 00:07:40.340
And I will say that our
moderator this evening is one

00:07:40.340 --> 00:07:44.440
of the first ones we had
in DC, Connie Morella.

00:07:44.440 --> 00:07:51.450
She's a great friend of NOIAW
and I don't think there's anyone

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:55.330
who doesn't know Connie
who's from this area.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:08:01.730
Anyway, if anyone is
actually interested or wants

00:08:01.730 --> 00:08:05.150
to know more, I have
more brochures

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:06.870
and I will give them to you.

00:08:06.870 --> 00:08:09.450
And I welcome you.

00:08:09.450 --> 00:08:15.330
I am so glad that some of
you managed to get here.

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:19.820
And I look forward
to this evening,

00:08:19.820 --> 00:08:23.650
because I'm very
interested in this topic.

00:08:23.650 --> 00:08:26.180
So thank you very much.

00:08:27.510 --> 00:08:42.100
[ Applause ]

00:08:42.100 --> 00:08:43.940
&gt;&gt; Lucia Wolfe: I am going to
be really brief because I want

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:47.830
to leave it to the speakers,
to the presenters tonight.

00:08:47.830 --> 00:08:49.460
So can you hear me?

00:08:49.460 --> 00:08:52.360
And I'm even shorter than Diana.

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:56.590
I am Lucia Wolfe and I'm
the reference librarian

00:08:56.590 --> 00:08:59.130
at the European Division
who is responsible

00:08:59.130 --> 00:09:01.180
for the Italian collections.

00:09:01.180 --> 00:09:04.630
And those are especially
the general collections;

00:09:04.630 --> 00:09:07.370
that is the books
and periodicals

00:09:07.370 --> 00:09:10.640
that are published
from 1801 onwards.

00:09:10.640 --> 00:09:15.110
So just to give you
an idea of the scope

00:09:15.110 --> 00:09:17.190
of the Italian collections,

00:09:17.190 --> 00:09:23.030
I will say that at large they
are 800,000 and more items.

00:09:23.030 --> 00:09:25.260
Not only the general
collections,

00:09:25.260 --> 00:09:27.730
but also other formats.

00:09:27.730 --> 00:09:29.490
We have prints and photographs.

00:09:29.490 --> 00:09:30.980
We have newspapers.

00:09:30.980 --> 00:09:33.070
We have manuscripts.

00:09:33.070 --> 00:09:38.460
I think I'm forgetting --
oh, music scores, webpages,

00:09:38.460 --> 00:09:42.920
sound recordings, motion
pictures and I could go on.

00:09:42.920 --> 00:09:47.160
Linda will do a better
job later.

00:09:47.160 --> 00:09:50.940
So I wanted to say that
because it gives you an idea

00:09:50.940 --> 00:09:53.840
of the scope of the Italian
collections in general.

00:09:53.840 --> 00:09:58.000
But for two years now I've
been trying to focus in also

00:09:58.000 --> 00:09:59.970
on the Italian American
collections.

00:09:59.970 --> 00:10:05.140
It is very hard to separate
the two collections,

00:10:05.140 --> 00:10:08.610
because for a great part in
the 19th century and beginning

00:10:08.610 --> 00:10:10.880
of the 20th century, many

00:10:10.880 --> 00:10:16.010
of the Italian American books
were actually printed in Italy

00:10:16.010 --> 00:10:18.460
and then printed
also in America.

00:10:18.460 --> 00:10:23.360
So I believe they're classifying
and dividing the Italian

00:10:23.360 --> 00:10:26.020
and the Italian American
collections at that point

00:10:26.020 --> 00:10:28.400
between the end of the 19th
century and the beginning

00:10:28.400 --> 00:10:31.720
of the 20th century
could be problematic.

00:10:31.720 --> 00:10:35.000
I have been working with some --

00:10:35.000 --> 00:10:40.530
we also hire some
wonderful interns and some

00:10:40.530 --> 00:10:44.210
of them will be outside
at the display.

00:10:44.210 --> 00:10:47.440
Mostly, I work with Italian
America interns from all

00:10:47.440 --> 00:10:50.600
over the United States
of America.

00:10:50.600 --> 00:10:54.130
And what we have been
doing lately is focus

00:10:54.130 --> 00:10:56.810
on the Italian American
periodicals,

00:10:56.810 --> 00:11:00.880
one of the most consistent
and extensive parts

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:05.250
of the collections, of the
Italian American collections.

00:11:05.250 --> 00:11:10.180
But we are also working on
collecting data about books

00:11:10.180 --> 00:11:12.720
and other items in
the collection.

00:11:12.720 --> 00:11:15.800
So I just wanted
to say that because

00:11:15.800 --> 00:11:19.200
in the next few years we will
also publish some research

00:11:19.200 --> 00:11:20.500
guides online.

00:11:20.500 --> 00:11:24.690
And for further information,
those will be very useful

00:11:24.690 --> 00:11:32.380
to orientate you about the
Italian American collections.

00:11:32.380 --> 00:11:35.490
Two words about the
display, I have tried

00:11:35.490 --> 00:11:37.720
to put together a display

00:11:37.720 --> 00:11:40.330
that represents the period
we are talking about,

00:11:40.330 --> 00:11:44.060
but I moved a little
bit onward to the 1970's

00:11:44.060 --> 00:11:46.170
and past the 1970's,

00:11:46.170 --> 00:11:50.510
so it doesn't really
reflect our theme completely.

00:11:50.510 --> 00:11:52.390
But there are various sections.

00:11:52.390 --> 00:11:57.580
The earliest section is about
books by politicians, statesmen,

00:11:57.580 --> 00:12:05.700
vice consuls from Italy
who traveled to America

00:12:05.700 --> 00:12:10.030
and in general try to do surveys

00:12:10.030 --> 00:12:12.640
and also record their
impressions

00:12:12.640 --> 00:12:15.170
of the Italian American
communities throughout a

00:12:15.170 --> 00:12:18.420
continent in some
interesting travel journals

00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:19.990
that you will see out there.

00:12:19.990 --> 00:12:24.270
Those books are principally in
Italian because there were a lot

00:12:24.270 --> 00:12:28.010
of Italian politicians and
diplomats who were coming

00:12:28.010 --> 00:12:31.400
in from Italy and
doing these surveys.

00:12:31.400 --> 00:12:35.570
The next group is
education and literacy.

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:37.800
I try to represent
that, number one,

00:12:37.800 --> 00:12:40.170
because I am biased
as a librarian.

00:12:40.170 --> 00:12:42.970
Many of the educators

00:12:42.970 --> 00:12:46.210
of the first Italian Americans
were actually librarians.

00:12:46.210 --> 00:12:50.420
And you will find out some of
the books and some of the prints

00:12:50.420 --> 00:12:53.220
and photographs identify this.

00:12:53.220 --> 00:12:57.080
So I am extremely
proud about that.

00:12:57.080 --> 00:13:03.170
And I have also highlighted
literature and art

00:13:03.170 --> 00:13:06.580
in Italian Americans'
interpretation.

00:13:06.580 --> 00:13:09.250
One case is the translation

00:13:09.250 --> 00:13:11.840
by John Chardy of
the Divine Comedy.

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:14.200
I did not include
that in the display

00:13:14.200 --> 00:13:15.910
because I needed to select.

00:13:15.910 --> 00:13:20.770
But I did include a beautiful
translation of the divine comedy

00:13:20.770 --> 00:13:26.270
with artwork by Umberto
Romano, a very important

00:13:26.270 --> 00:13:30.790
and particular original
Italian American artist.

00:13:30.790 --> 00:13:34.320
I don't want to go on for
too long, but I did want

00:13:34.320 --> 00:13:38.200
to highlight how the
display moves through time.

00:13:38.200 --> 00:13:41.710
And I included some photographs

00:13:41.710 --> 00:13:46.480
that also Lind has shown
in her splendid book.

00:13:46.480 --> 00:13:51.140
Some of the photos I displayed
are not in Linda's book

00:13:51.140 --> 00:13:52.870
because I didn't
want to overlap.

00:13:52.870 --> 00:13:57.410
So I hope you will take
some time and enjoy

00:13:57.410 --> 00:13:58.810
and look at the display.

00:13:58.810 --> 00:14:02.190
And I will be out
there to explain

00:14:02.190 --> 00:14:03.490
and answer your questions.

00:14:03.490 --> 00:14:10.510
Thank you very much and
now to the speakers.

