00:18:14.270 --> 00:18:19.500
The theme, Italian Americans
before and during World War II.

00:18:19.500 --> 00:18:22.650
And it's very timely.

00:18:22.650 --> 00:18:24.750
And as a matter of
fact, I was thinking,

00:18:24.750 --> 00:18:27.030
having been on the Battle
Monuments Commission,

00:18:27.030 --> 00:18:31.490
this is the 100th anniversary
of the end of World War I.

00:18:31.490 --> 00:18:36.860
Remember, that was the war
to end all wars, right?

00:18:36.860 --> 00:18:41.890
And personal disclosure
on my part,

00:18:41.890 --> 00:18:44.530
my parents were both
born in Italy.

00:18:44.530 --> 00:18:47.130
So I am first-generation.

00:18:47.130 --> 00:18:50.320
My three older brothers
all served

00:18:50.320 --> 00:18:56.650
in the United States
Army during World War II.

00:18:56.650 --> 00:19:00.000
I was much younger,
but nevertheless,

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:03.120
my parents would have
me write those V mail.

00:19:03.120 --> 00:19:07.400
Anybody remember V mail?

00:19:07.400 --> 00:19:09.550
My mother would dictate to
me, "I want you to write

00:19:09.550 --> 00:19:10.920
to your brothers and I want you

00:19:10.920 --> 00:19:13.060
to tell them this
and tell them that."

00:19:13.060 --> 00:19:16.920
And so we operated that way
and we were very proud to have

00:19:16.920 --> 00:19:22.040
on our window that flag
with the three blue stars.

00:19:22.040 --> 00:19:23.500
Thank God they weren't gold,

00:19:23.500 --> 00:19:27.840
but the three blue stars all
commemorating World War II.

00:19:27.840 --> 00:19:33.140
So I'm just so very honored
that we have this event tonight

00:19:33.140 --> 00:19:37.760
so that we can look back, we can
reflect and we can move ahead.

00:19:37.760 --> 00:19:41.570
Our first speaker is
Linda Barrett Osborne.

00:19:41.570 --> 00:19:47.030
She's an award-winning
writer, editor, book reviewer

00:19:47.030 --> 00:19:50.100
for the Washington Post
and the New York Times,

00:19:50.100 --> 00:19:53.630
and a senior writer/editor
for the publishing office

00:19:53.630 --> 00:19:56.270
of the Library of Congress.

00:19:56.270 --> 00:19:59.110
She has received
numerous awards,

00:19:59.110 --> 00:20:03.100
such as the Penn
Syndicated Fiction Award.

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:04.880
She's authored a
collection of books

00:20:04.880 --> 00:20:07.540
for school students and adults.

00:20:07.540 --> 00:20:10.380
I love the titles of them,
because they say so much

00:20:10.380 --> 00:20:14.360
about her and how she
feels about our country.

00:20:14.360 --> 00:20:17.250
For instance, This
Land is Our Land.

00:20:17.250 --> 00:20:22.650
Come On In, America
is another one.

00:20:22.650 --> 00:20:26.370
Miles to Go for Freedom
is another one.

00:20:26.370 --> 00:20:29.870
Traveling the Freedom
Road is another.

00:20:29.870 --> 00:20:34.990
And to me, they show her
love and promise of America.

00:20:34.990 --> 00:20:38.430
We feel particularly close
tonight to the thesis

00:20:38.430 --> 00:20:43.970
of the book that she coauthored
called Explorers, Immigrants,

00:20:43.970 --> 00:20:50.330
Citizens: A Visual Look at the
Italian American Experience.

00:20:50.330 --> 00:20:56.370
As Shakespeare wrote, a beggar's
book outworths a noble's blood.

00:20:56.370 --> 00:20:59.690
And I think you have
