a country to 2015.

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:40.500
And it deals not only
with Italian Americans,

00:22:40.500 --> 00:22:45.250
but with every ethnic
group, Asians, Latinos

00:22:45.250 --> 00:22:46.910
and refugees as a group.

00:22:46.910 --> 00:22:50.700
And one on the United
States in World War I.

00:22:50.700 --> 00:22:56.400
And I am now working on a book
on the history and the meaning

00:22:56.400 --> 00:22:59.140
of freedom of the
press in this country.

00:22:59.140 --> 00:23:03.270
I like to do books
that deal with some

00:23:03.270 --> 00:23:06.870
of the more negative
aspects of American history.

00:23:06.870 --> 00:23:10.130
And that as I understand
it, is what I'm going

00:23:10.130 --> 00:23:11.970
to talk about tonight.

00:23:11.970 --> 00:23:13.860
I want you to know
that my books are full

00:23:13.860 --> 00:23:19.240
of the positive experiences
of American history.

00:23:19.240 --> 00:23:24.790
Because I am always amazed
and impressed by the way

00:23:24.790 --> 00:23:28.880
that any group -- African
Americans for some of my books,

00:23:28.880 --> 00:23:32.390
Italian American immigrants --

00:23:32.390 --> 00:23:34.610
have overcome the obstacles

00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:37.970
that have been placed
before them to succeed.

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:39.940
And so as I say,
it's a combination,

00:23:39.940 --> 00:23:43.700
but without knowing exactly
what they had to overcome,

00:23:43.700 --> 00:23:47.120
I don't think we get a complete
history of the United States.

00:23:47.120 --> 00:23:50.010
One more thing about
the Library of Congress,

00:23:50.010 --> 00:23:54.090
the Jefferson building was
put together pretty much

00:23:54.090 --> 00:23:56.950
by Italian artisans.

00:23:56.950 --> 00:23:58.950
In fact, a lot of
the public monuments

00:23:58.950 --> 00:24:03.030
in this country were done
by people who had the skills

00:24:03.030 --> 00:24:04.620
who were brought
over from Italy.

00:24:04.620 --> 00:24:09.210
That's one of the positive
things in the book.

00:24:09.210 --> 00:24:15.970
Anyway, I will start now
with my talk with a photo.

00:24:15.970 --> 00:24:17.270
I hope I get this right.

00:24:17.270 --> 00:24:19.740
Did it go?

00:24:23.040 --> 00:24:24.340
Now I did this --
oh there we go.

00:24:24.340 --> 00:24:25.640
This is a photo

00:24:25.640 --> 00:24:28.300
of my great-grandfather,
Nicolas Faleri.

00:24:28.300 --> 00:24:30.350
Let me explain the Bocucci part.

00:24:30.350 --> 00:24:34.640
My parents actually
changed their names in 1941,

00:24:34.640 --> 00:24:36.620
'42, before I was born.

00:24:36.620 --> 00:24:38.290
So I was never Linda Bocucci.

00:24:38.290 --> 00:24:40.190
I was always Linda Barrett.

00:24:40.190 --> 00:24:45.340
But all of my great-grandparents
came here from Italy

00:24:45.340 --> 00:24:46.640
and I will explain that.

00:24:46.640 --> 00:24:48.940
This is Nicolas Faleri.

00:24:56.290 --> 00:24:59.270
Yeah, and this is his wife
Josephine Faleri who was one

00:24:59.270 --> 00:25:01.160
of my great-grandmothers.

00:25:01.160 --> 00:25:02.620
And as I said, the
immigrated here

00:25:02.620 --> 00:25:04.960
from Bologna in the
19th century.

00:25:04.960 --> 00:25:06.260
Now all eight

00:25:06.260 --> 00:25:07.690
of my great-grandparents
were Italian immigrants.

00:25:07.690 --> 00:25:11.420
So the Bocucci's, the
Moreno's and the Charoni's.

00:25:11.420 --> 00:25:13.840
The reason the name was
changed in the 1940's was

00:25:13.840 --> 00:25:17.910
that my father felt that he was
being discriminated at work.

00:25:17.910 --> 00:25:21.190
He was working for General
Motors, an American company.

00:25:21.190 --> 00:25:23.360
Anyway, whether that
was true or not,

00:25:23.360 --> 00:25:26.330
it was very common unfortunately
for Italian Americans

00:25:26.330 --> 00:25:29.530
to change their name in that
period and to try better

00:25:29.530 --> 00:25:36.300
to assimilate into the
model of a pure American

00:25:36.300 --> 00:25:39.680
which also included I'm
afraid losing the language.

00:25:39.680 --> 00:25:43.590
But not the food or parts
of the culture, okay.

00:25:43.590 --> 00:25:49.440
Now, my great-grandparents
came in the 1880's or 1890's.

00:25:49.440 --> 00:25:51.290
And I show you these
because the story

00:25:51.290 --> 00:25:55.010
of Italian immigration is
personal to m. You see,

00:25:55.010 --> 00:25:58.760
they are not just
statistics or stereotypes.

00:25:58.760 --> 00:26:00.060
These are my family.

00:26:00.060 --> 00:26:03.170
This is my heritage and that
might be a good thing to keep

00:26:03.170 --> 00:26:06.520
in mind when we think about
immigration in general

00:26:06.520 --> 00:26:10.120
in this country and
in the world.

00:26:10.120 --> 00:26:13.020
A large influx of Italian
Americans to this country began

00:26:13.020 --> 00:26:18.030
in about 1870 when most of Italy
north and south became united.

00:26:18.030 --> 00:26:20.320
And although you might expect
conditions to have improved,

00:26:20.320 --> 00:26:22.210
they actually worsened
in southern Italy.

00:26:22.210 --> 00:26:24.930
The country was ruled from
Piedmont to the north.

00:26:24.930 --> 00:26:27.310
I won't get into Italian
politics at the time.

00:26:27.310 --> 00:26:30.310
But they considered the
south somewhat barbarous.

00:26:30.310 --> 00:26:33.570
And they imposed higher taxes
on basics like mules and salt

00:26:33.570 --> 00:26:35.520
and unemployment was rampant.

00:26:35.520 --> 00:26:39.010
Extreme poverty, that's
what drove tens of thousands

00:26:39.010 --> 00:26:42.240
to leave southern Italy to
find economic opportunity

00:26:42.240 --> 00:26:44.190
in the United States.

00:26:44.190 --> 00:26:46.980
Now leaving Italy was not easy.

00:26:46.980 --> 00:26:50.210
It meant leaving home,
family and culture behind.

00:26:50.210 --> 00:26:53.010
It took a great deal of courage.

00:26:57.280 --> 00:26:59.480
Most immigrants, and
as far as I know,

00:26:59.480 --> 00:27:01.070
all eight of my
great-grandparents,

00:27:01.070 --> 00:27:03.500
came by steamboat at steeridge.

00:27:03.500 --> 00:27:07.250
The average time at sea in
the 1890's was 7-10 days.

00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:10.120
In the 1860's it was
something like 51 days.

00:27:10.120 --> 00:27:13.200
So the passage had improved.

00:27:13.200 --> 00:27:17.440
Now, passage in steeridge, which
is the third and lowest class

00:27:17.440 --> 00:27:21.730
of travel, is almost universally
acknowledged to be miserable.

00:27:21.730 --> 00:27:26.370
In 1907, a Neopolitan
immigrant wrote,

00:27:26.370 --> 00:27:28.980
"How can a steward's
passenger remember

00:27:28.980 --> 00:27:32.420
that he is a human being when
he first must pick the worms

00:27:32.420 --> 00:27:35.940
from his food and eat in
a stuffy, stinking bunk

00:27:35.940 --> 00:27:37.960
or in the hot and
fetid atmosphere

00:27:37.960 --> 00:27:41.130
of a compartment
where 150 men sleep?"

00:27:41.130 --> 00:27:44.320
I love using direct
quotes and stories,

00:27:44.320 --> 00:27:46.280
interviews, primary sources.

00:27:46.280 --> 00:27:48.790
There will be a bunch
of them in this talk.

00:27:48.790 --> 00:27:52.740
It's not just me saying
that it was tough to cross.

00:27:52.740 --> 00:27:54.870
It's the person who
actually did that.

00:27:54.870 --> 00:27:57.350
And I see my great-grandparents
too,

00:27:57.350 --> 00:28:00.500
telling you what it was like,
what the experience was like.

00:28:00.500 --> 00:28:09.740
However, nothing -- not even
the miserable ocean-crossing --

00:28:09.740 --> 00:28:12.570
engendered more fear in
immigrants than the possibility

00:28:12.570 --> 00:28:13.870
that they would be turned away

00:28:13.870 --> 00:28:16.690
at Ellis Island when
they arrived.

00:28:18.130 --> 00:28:21.340
It's also interesting to
me that if you came second

00:28:21.340 --> 00:28:25.720
or first class, you went
directly into the United States

00:28:25.720 --> 00:28:28.270
without going through
inspection stations.

00:28:28.270 --> 00:28:30.280
It was assumed that
you had enough money

00:28:30.280 --> 00:28:32.670
and that you would never
become a public charge,

00:28:32.670 --> 00:28:33.970
which was a big fear

00:28:33.970 --> 00:28:38.450
of Americans living
here at the time.

00:28:38.450 --> 00:28:40.750
Okay?

00:28:43.420 --> 00:28:45.080
The new arrivals
were most afraid

00:28:45.080 --> 00:28:47.180
of the medical examination.

00:28:47.180 --> 00:28:50.090
Here they are being
examined for traucoma

00:28:50.090 --> 00:28:53.840
which was an eye disease which
is the illness or disease

00:28:53.840 --> 00:28:56.100
that sent most of them back.

00:28:56.100 --> 00:28:59.550
I'm going to have a quote
from Forello Laguardia

00:28:59.550 --> 00:29:01.180
who actually worked
as an interpreter

00:29:01.180 --> 00:29:03.470
on Ellis Island when
he was young.

00:29:03.470 --> 00:29:07.150
"Many were found to be
suffering from traucoma,

00:29:07.150 --> 00:29:09.860
and their exclusion
was mandatory.

00:29:09.860 --> 00:29:12.870
It was harrowing to
see families separated.

00:29:12.870 --> 00:29:15.380
Sometimes, if it was a
young child who suffered

00:29:15.380 --> 00:29:18.030
from traucoma, one of
the parents had to return

00:29:18.030 --> 00:29:21.210
to the native country with the
rejected member of the family.

00:29:21.210 --> 00:29:23.090
When they learned this
fate, they were stunned.

00:29:23.090 --> 00:29:27.380
They could see all right, and
they had no homes to return to."

00:29:27.380 --> 00:29:32.960
Now if you came after
1886 when the Statue

00:29:32.960 --> 00:29:35.790
of Liberty was dedicated --
that's actually fairly late

00:29:35.790 --> 00:29:39.510
and Ellis Island didn't
open until 1892 --

00:29:39.510 --> 00:29:41.160
you were greeted by the Lady.

00:29:41.160 --> 00:29:43.390
Once you made it into
the country, however,

00:29:43.390 --> 00:29:45.810
unfortunately most
Italian immigrants were met

00:29:45.810 --> 00:29:48.170
with prejudice and
discrimination.

00:29:48.170 --> 00:29:51.950
And this is an Italian
family arriving in the period

00:29:51.950 --> 00:29:55.020
around the turn of the century.

00:29:55.020 --> 00:29:57.100
Not only Italians, but Jews

00:29:57.100 --> 00:30:00.190
and Slavs among many
Americans in this period.

00:30:00.190 --> 00:30:03.120
Earlier, Germans and Irish
immigrants had alarmed

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:04.510
many Americans.

00:30:04.510 --> 00:30:07.830
Later, Asians and Latinos would.

00:30:07.830 --> 00:30:13.080
Right? That's a theme throughout
our country's history, okay?

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:18.910
It's politicians, the
press and the public,

00:30:18.910 --> 00:30:22.480
wide socioeconomic
variety of people,

00:30:22.480 --> 00:30:27.530
who called for preserving
the United States

00:30:27.530 --> 00:30:32.340
for English descendants of
what they called Anglo-Saxons.

00:30:33.730 --> 00:30:40.190
Okay. These people who were
against immigration by people

00:30:40.190 --> 00:30:41.850
from many, many countries,

00:30:41.850 --> 00:30:43.540
called themselves
native Americans.

00:30:43.540 --> 00:30:46.930
This was before we used native
Americans the way we do now.

00:30:46.930 --> 00:30:49.290
This was in the 19th century.

00:30:49.290 --> 00:30:50.850
And those who opposed
immigration

00:30:50.850 --> 00:30:53.650
by any other ethnic group
were called nativists.

00:30:53.650 --> 00:30:58.490
And I sometimes use that as a
quick way of describing people

00:30:58.490 --> 00:31:02.190
in this country against -- well,
Americans who were born here

00:31:02.190 --> 00:31:03.650
who believe that only people

00:31:03.650 --> 00:31:06.940
of Anglo-Saxon heritage
can become real Americans.

00:31:06.940 --> 00:31:09.370
These are lodged members.

00:31:09.370 --> 00:31:11.290
In 1902, they are dressed

00:31:11.290 --> 00:31:16.550
in what they believed
was Anglo-Saxon costume.

00:31:16.550 --> 00:31:19.160
And they were serious
about this.

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:21.770
They also felt that
the traditions

00:31:21.770 --> 00:31:24.580
of English government
were the only traditions

00:31:24.580 --> 00:31:26.430
that were worth preserving
in this country.

00:31:26.430 --> 00:31:29.560
Okay, nativists thought
that the flood of eastern

00:31:29.560 --> 00:31:33.370
and southern European immigrants
which started in the 1870's

00:31:33.370 --> 00:31:36.740
and continued into World War
I could never be assimilated

00:31:36.740 --> 00:31:39.920
into American society
and culture.

00:31:39.920 --> 00:31:43.080
Okay? These newcomers
looked different, dressed

00:31:43.080 --> 00:31:45.240
and spoke differently,
lived in crime-

00:31:45.240 --> 00:31:47.370
and disease-ridden,
filthy neighborhoods.

00:31:47.370 --> 00:31:50.140
And never mind that most
Americans didn't want them

00:31:50.140 --> 00:31:51.740
in their own neighborhoods.

00:31:51.740 --> 00:31:53.800
And one of many examples used

00:31:53.800 --> 00:31:56.220
to describe Italian Americans
appeared in the Review

00:31:56.220 --> 00:31:58.830
of Reviews in 1891,
which called them,

00:31:58.830 --> 00:32:02.860
"The refuse of the murder
reeds of southern Europe."

00:32:02.860 --> 00:32:04.170
These are my great-grandparents,

00:32:04.170 --> 00:32:07.890
and this is the time
they were coming.

00:32:07.890 --> 00:32:12.120
Many Italian immigrants
stayed in New York.

00:32:12.120 --> 00:32:21.520
A classic scene of tenements in
Little Italy in New York City.

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:23.420
And almost universally,

00:32:23.420 --> 00:32:24.920
they lived in immigrant
neighborhoods.

00:32:24.920 --> 00:32:27.380
And this was partly because
they were more comfortable

00:32:27.380 --> 00:32:30.310
and secure living with
others from their hometowns.

00:32:30.310 --> 00:32:32.720
And of course partly because
most Americans did not welcome

00:32:32.720 --> 00:32:34.490
them in their neighborhoods.

00:32:34.490 --> 00:32:39.020
Living inside Little Italy's
had serious disadvantages.

00:32:39.020 --> 00:32:42.540
It isolated Italian
immigrants from other Americans.

00:32:42.540 --> 00:32:44.650
They could avoid
learning to speak English

00:32:44.650 --> 00:32:46.920
or adopt American customs.

00:32:46.920 --> 00:32:50.620
And it limited their
opportunities, okay?

00:32:50.620 --> 00:32:51.920
But here's a happy one.

00:32:51.920 --> 00:32:53.220
I snuck in a happy one.

00:32:53.220 --> 00:32:55.110
This is a festival
in Little Italy.

00:32:55.110 --> 00:32:58.940
In fact, I could give
a whole other talk

00:32:58.940 --> 00:33:03.190
on how wonderful the Italian
American culture developed,

00:33:03.190 --> 00:33:06.160
not only in New York, but
cities across the United States

00:33:06.160 --> 00:33:07.830
and even in small towns.

00:33:07.830 --> 00:33:10.540
Just to give you an
idea of the crowding --

00:33:10.540 --> 00:33:15.550
well, I'm about to give
a quote about the men

00:33:15.550 --> 00:33:17.530
who lived in Little Italy.

00:33:17.530 --> 00:33:18.830
This is interesting.

00:33:18.830 --> 00:33:20.840
I don't know if you can see it.

00:33:20.840 --> 00:33:24.090
This was also during a festival,
guys staying on the streets.

00:33:24.090 --> 00:33:26.200
The tenements were
above the shops.

00:33:26.200 --> 00:33:29.410
There's a giant candle
on the left side

00:33:29.410 --> 00:33:32.310
of the photograph,
and the right.

00:33:32.310 --> 00:33:35.160
And they were carried
in the festivals.

00:33:35.160 --> 00:33:37.690
So I thought it was
a need picture.

00:33:37.690 --> 00:33:41.770
In any case, whether they
were learning English or not,

00:33:41.770 --> 00:33:43.970
whether they were being
assimilated or not,

00:33:43.970 --> 00:33:46.360
the immigrants when they
first arrived worked the

00:33:46.360 --> 00:33:48.350
poorest-paying jobs
and were crowded

00:33:48.350 --> 00:33:51.110
into the poorest
slum neighborhoods.

00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:53.850
And malnutrition affected
children in adults.

00:33:53.850 --> 00:33:58.340
In 1908, one Italian write
pictured, "A little Colavia

00:33:58.340 --> 00:34:00.560
across the ocean where
immigrants returned

00:34:00.560 --> 00:34:03.770
to their homes, and after
a very frugal meal go

00:34:03.770 --> 00:34:05.330
to their poor beds huddled

00:34:05.330 --> 00:34:07.620
against each other
for little rest.

00:34:07.620 --> 00:34:09.500
Everyone can imagine
how these tired

00:34:09.500 --> 00:34:12.770
and undernourished beings
might easily develop the germs

00:34:12.770 --> 00:34:16.320
of diseases, especially
tuberculosis."

00:34:16.320 --> 00:34:19.900
Jacob Reese who was a journalist
and social reformer noted,

00:34:19.900 --> 00:34:24.790
"In a block of tenements
which totaled 132 rooms,

00:34:24.790 --> 00:34:28.660
1,342 Italian immigrants lived.

00:34:28.660 --> 00:34:31.690
Mostly men, Sicilian
laborers, sleeping more

00:34:31.690 --> 00:34:35.400
than 10 people per room
for an entire block."

00:34:37.150 --> 00:34:39.560
Okay. Okay, in New
York's tenements in tiny,

00:34:39.560 --> 00:34:42.860
overcrowded apartments, women
and children did piece work.

00:34:42.860 --> 00:34:48.420
There's an apartment
in New York.

00:34:48.420 --> 00:34:49.720
There the kids are not working.

00:34:49.720 --> 00:34:51.280
In my next picture,
they will be.

00:34:51.280 --> 00:34:54.510
And they often sewed
garments or notion sequins,

00:34:54.510 --> 00:34:56.830
feathers, all kinds of things.

00:34:56.830 --> 00:35:00.150
All the children and the
women, to support families.

00:35:03.120 --> 00:35:06.820
Okay, another one
with everybody sitting

00:35:06.820 --> 00:35:10.160
around the table working.

00:35:14.040 --> 00:35:17.530
The National Child Labor
Committee described one woman

00:35:17.530 --> 00:35:20.780
of the hundreds and
thousands who did this,

00:35:20.780 --> 00:35:23.080
living in "a poverty-stricken
home

00:35:23.080 --> 00:35:25.730
and making a pittance
for finishing pants."

00:35:25.730 --> 00:35:29.200
Now child labor was common in
the late 1800's and early 1900's

00:35:29.200 --> 00:35:34.450
and even after World War I, not
only among Italian immigrants.

00:35:34.450 --> 00:35:40.240
For poverty-stricken
families, this was a necessity.

00:35:40.240 --> 00:35:44.160
This picture shows a group --
I have many pictures outside

00:35:44.160 --> 00:35:48.770
of New York in the book,
but here is one of them

00:35:48.770 --> 00:35:51.160
in Mississippi in 1911.

00:35:51.160 --> 00:35:55.410
And the youngest worker
standing on the box,

00:35:55.410 --> 00:35:58.130
you can see, is five years old.

00:35:58.130 --> 00:36:01.450
Okay. Nativists and even
many other Americans

00:36:01.450 --> 00:36:05.750
who were less politically vocal
held four widespread stereotypes

00:36:05.750 --> 00:36:07.870
about Italian Americans.

00:36:07.870 --> 00:36:10.770
They were Catholic,
which isn't a stereotype;

00:36:10.770 --> 00:36:12.650
it was perceived as a problem.

00:36:12.650 --> 00:36:20.790
Sorry. Ignorant, criminals and
anarchists or labor agitators.

00:36:20.790 --> 00:36:22.990
Nativists were extremely
anti-Catholic

00:36:22.990 --> 00:36:26.640
and they believed Americans
should be Protestant.

00:36:26.640 --> 00:36:29.310
Here's an example of an
altar in an Italian church.

00:36:29.310 --> 00:36:31.070
This is not Protestant.

00:36:31.070 --> 00:36:36.350
The idea of fests

00:36:36.350 --> 00:36:43.750
and celebrating saints
was a little too exuberant

00:36:43.750 --> 00:36:46.520
for many traditional Americans.

00:36:46.520 --> 00:36:51.560
In any case, nativists also
believed there was a papal plot

00:36:51.560 --> 00:36:54.170
to take over the United States.

00:36:54.170 --> 00:36:56.570
And I can't show you all
the illustrations I have

00:36:56.570 --> 00:37:00.590
of our cartoons showing the
pope about to devour Manhattan.

00:37:00.590 --> 00:37:04.490
But one of the things
they worried about was

00:37:04.490 --> 00:37:07.260
that Catholic influence would
menace American traditions

00:37:07.260 --> 00:37:11.160
such as public education
because many Catholics went

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:12.460
to Catholic schools.

00:37:12.460 --> 00:37:17.570
However, most Italian kids
actually went to public schools.

00:37:17.570 --> 00:37:21.880
I wish I could spend more
time on it, but you know,

00:37:21.880 --> 00:37:23.750
even as late as 1960,

00:37:23.750 --> 00:37:27.170
John Kennedy was
considered possibly nonviable

00:37:27.170 --> 00:37:30.070
as a president because
he was Catholic.

00:37:30.070 --> 00:37:32.610
So this was a persistent
stereotype

00:37:32.610 --> 00:37:35.480
that covers more than Italians.

00:37:35.480 --> 00:37:38.270
Now the Italian organ-grinder,

00:37:38.270 --> 00:37:40.770
which is entertainment
during the early decades

00:37:40.770 --> 00:37:44.120
of mass immigration, became
a stereotype reflecting an

00:37:44.120 --> 00:37:47.020
unsophisticated, even
base foreign culture.

00:37:47.020 --> 00:37:51.090
And the Italian accent when
speaking English was mocked.

00:37:51.090 --> 00:37:54.100
One example, in the
silent movie, The Italian,

00:37:54.100 --> 00:37:55.780
which was produced by
an American company

00:37:55.780 --> 00:37:57.970
that had absolutely no
involvement with Italians

00:37:57.970 --> 00:38:00.520
or Italian Americans,
the dialogue appeared

00:38:00.520 --> 00:38:05.420
to be a mashed-up English,
supposedly spoken by Italians.

00:38:05.420 --> 00:38:07.070
Not sure I can even
say this right.

00:38:07.070 --> 00:38:10.770
"I must geta dee milk
or my babe is die."

00:38:10.770 --> 00:38:15.390
And that's the image that
many people had of us.

00:38:15.390 --> 00:38:18.190
Probably the most damaging
and persistent stereotype was

00:38:18.190 --> 00:38:20.810
of southern Italians as violent.

00:38:20.810 --> 00:38:24.310
"The disposition to
assassinate in revenge

00:38:24.310 --> 00:38:27.290
for a fancied wrong is a
marked trait of the character

00:38:27.290 --> 00:38:30.020
of this impulsive
and inexorable race."

00:38:30.020 --> 00:38:32.580
That's the Baltimore
News in the 1890's.

00:38:32.580 --> 00:38:34.560
We're not just talking
about fringe elements.

00:38:34.560 --> 00:38:38.590
We're talking about mainstream
press saying these things

00:38:38.590 --> 00:38:41.270
about us.

00:38:41.270 --> 00:38:44.200
Okay. The strength
and pervasiveness

00:38:44.200 --> 00:38:46.000
of criminal organizations
like the Black Hand

00:38:46.000 --> 00:38:48.680
and the Mafia however,
were vastly exaggerated,

00:38:48.680 --> 00:38:51.030
especially by the news media.

00:38:51.030 --> 00:38:53.530
Sensational stories
fed on public prejudice

00:38:53.530 --> 00:38:55.750
at the same time
they reinforced it.

00:38:55.750 --> 00:38:59.690
They were more interesting I
think to sell copies of papers

00:38:59.690 --> 00:39:01.680
than Vermini's Capital.

00:39:01.680 --> 00:39:04.960
You know, a painting
in the capital.

00:39:04.960 --> 00:39:07.020
These stereotypes were
exposed officially.

00:39:07.020 --> 00:39:12.000
In this cartoon,
rats -- see them --

00:39:12.000 --> 00:39:14.460
representing different
countries leaves the shores

00:39:14.460 --> 00:39:15.760
of the old world.

00:39:15.760 --> 00:39:17.060
The European leaders

00:39:17.060 --> 00:39:19.570
on the shore are
delighted to see them go.

00:39:19.570 --> 00:39:24.200
The one in the foreground,
the very front in the middle,

00:39:24.200 --> 00:39:31.600
holds the infamous letter of the
Black Hand between his teeth.

00:39:31.600 --> 00:39:34.260
Soon, the Black Hand became
synonymous with crime,

00:39:34.260 --> 00:39:35.730
particularly Italian crime

00:39:35.730 --> 00:39:38.940
and Italians were actually
treated as criminals.

00:39:38.940 --> 00:39:43.560
In March 1891, 11 Italians
in New Orleans accused

00:39:43.560 --> 00:39:46.480
of murdering the local
police chief were lynched

00:39:46.480 --> 00:39:49.430
after a jury had
acquitted them of a crime.

00:39:49.430 --> 00:39:51.620
Okay. The event led
to the suspension

00:39:51.620 --> 00:39:54.680
of diplomatic relations between
Italy and the United States,

00:39:54.680 --> 00:39:58.680
the only time in history before
World War II that that happened.

00:39:58.680 --> 00:40:02.140
Lynching Italians was all too
frequent in the American south

00:40:02.140 --> 00:40:05.140
in the late 19th and
early 20th centuries.

00:40:05.140 --> 00:40:08.590
They hold the unenviable
record for the most lynchings

00:40:08.590 --> 00:40:12.720
of any ethnic group
after African Americans.

00:40:12.720 --> 00:40:14.890
I can give you a lot
of other examples,

00:40:14.890 --> 00:40:17.920
but not now with my time limit.

00:40:17.920 --> 00:40:21.040
Early Italian immigrants also
included political exiles

00:40:21.040 --> 00:40:22.710
who had fought for Italian unity

00:40:22.710 --> 00:40:24.730
and against monarchist
governments,

00:40:24.730 --> 00:40:27.670
and they were anarchists
and workers

00:40:27.670 --> 00:40:30.780
who became a strong
voice in union organizing

00:40:30.780 --> 00:40:32.790
and the American labor movement.

00:40:32.790 --> 00:40:37.210
Both were viewed as
disruptive and dangerous.

00:40:37.210 --> 00:40:40.340
This picture shows Joseph
Caruso, Joseph Ature,

00:40:40.340 --> 00:40:44.210
and Arturao Juvenicci who
were trade unionists arrested

00:40:44.210 --> 00:40:48.220
on false charges for murdering
actually an Italian worker

00:40:48.220 --> 00:40:50.880
protestor, Anilo Proso,
during the Lawrence,

00:40:50.880 --> 00:40:53.650
Massachusetts textile
strike of 1912.

00:40:53.650 --> 00:40:56.320
Ature was one of the
promotors of the strike.

00:40:56.320 --> 00:40:58.710
According to a Chicago
newspaper,

00:40:58.710 --> 00:41:01.680
it was "chiefly the
result of his efforts

00:41:01.680 --> 00:41:05.330
that 275,000 New England
textile mill workers are getting

00:41:05.330 --> 00:41:06.820
better wages."

00:41:06.820 --> 00:41:09.860
The mill owners had put Joe in
jail to get him out of the way.

00:41:09.860 --> 00:41:12.990
And the three were kept in
jail for several months even

00:41:12.990 --> 00:41:14.290
after the strike ended.

00:41:14.290 --> 00:41:15.810
And again, when they
finally went

00:41:15.810 --> 00:41:18.590
to trial, they were acquitted.

00:41:18.590 --> 00:41:21.870
So they weren't doing the things
they were being accused of,

00:41:21.870 --> 00:41:24.360
partly for political reasons.

00:41:24.360 --> 00:41:26.220
In the early 20th century,

00:41:26.220 --> 00:41:28.380
agitation to restrict
immigration grew,

00:41:28.380 --> 00:41:30.430
and some groups were thought
to be unassimilatable.

00:41:30.430 --> 00:41:34.840
By the time of World War I,
which the US entered in 1917,

00:41:34.840 --> 00:41:37.750
many Americans had come to
believe that if a person thought

00:41:37.750 --> 00:41:40.640
of themselves as a German
American or Irish American

00:41:40.640 --> 00:41:43.870
or obviously Italian
American instead of totally

00:41:43.870 --> 00:41:46.710
as an American, he or she
would not be fully loyal

00:41:46.710 --> 00:41:48.390
to the United States.

00:41:48.390 --> 00:41:51.020
Theodore Roosevelt said
that all true Americans,

00:41:51.020 --> 00:41:54.500
no matter where they were born,
should believe in "the simple

00:41:54.500 --> 00:41:57.870
and loyal motto,
America for Americans."

00:41:57.870 --> 00:42:03.090
And the idea of 100% Americanism
left little room for immigrants

00:42:03.090 --> 00:42:06.030
who could not adapt
quickly to American ways.

00:42:06.030 --> 00:42:08.420
I'm hoping you'll
see the parallel

00:42:08.420 --> 00:42:11.850
in the things I'm quoting

00:42:11.850 --> 00:42:13.750
without making a
big point about it.

00:42:13.750 --> 00:42:15.800
That's what amazed me

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:18.870
when I first started
doing this research.

00:42:18.870 --> 00:42:21.920
The same issues and
the same problems

00:42:21.920 --> 00:42:26.660
and the same language
have been used for 250 --

00:42:26.660 --> 00:42:28.770
even before we became
the United States.

00:42:28.770 --> 00:42:33.130
Benjamin Franklin complained
that the German immigrants --

00:42:33.130 --> 00:42:36.940
this is 1752 -- were
ruining Pennsylvania

00:42:36.940 --> 00:42:38.850
because they wouldn't
learn the English language

00:42:38.850 --> 00:42:40.160
and they had their own schools.

00:42:40.160 --> 00:42:44.630
Anyway, there were many attempts
to restrict or halt immigration

00:42:44.630 --> 00:42:46.210
from undesirable countries.

00:42:46.210 --> 00:42:50.450
Unfortunately, Italy was one of
them in the early 20th century.

00:42:50.450 --> 00:42:54.840
And the first significant
drive focused on passing a law

00:42:54.840 --> 00:42:57.270
that could keep immigrants
who could not read or write

00:42:57.270 --> 00:43:00.970
from entering the country.

00:43:00.970 --> 00:43:03.820
There, okay.

00:43:03.820 --> 00:43:06.470
Massachusetts Senator
Henry Cavetlage called

00:43:06.470 --> 00:43:10.470
for a literacy test
as early as 1896.

00:43:10.470 --> 00:43:13.890
His quote, "The literacy test
will bear most heavily upon the

00:43:13.890 --> 00:43:17.370
Italians, Russians, Poles,
Hungarians, Greeks and Asiatics

00:43:17.370 --> 00:43:21.100
and very lightly or not at all
upon English-speaking immigrants

00:43:21.100 --> 00:43:23.760
or German, Scandinavian
and French.

00:43:23.760 --> 00:43:25.760
In other words, the
races most affected

00:43:25.760 --> 00:43:28.230
by the literacy test are
those whose immigration

00:43:28.230 --> 00:43:31.150
to this country has begun
within the last 20 years

00:43:31.150 --> 00:43:34.150
and swelled rapidly to
enormous proportions,

00:43:34.150 --> 00:43:38.400
races who are most alien to
the great body of the people

00:43:38.400 --> 00:43:40.210
of the United States."

00:43:40.210 --> 00:43:45.140
Okay. I want to say
two things about this.

00:43:45.140 --> 00:43:47.430
One is that the literacy
test did not have

00:43:47.430 --> 00:43:48.730
to be passed in English.

00:43:48.730 --> 00:43:51.370
It could be passed
in your own language.

00:43:51.370 --> 00:43:55.050
Two is that women did not
have to pass the literacy test

00:43:55.050 --> 00:43:56.360
if they were accompanied
by a man.

00:43:56.360 --> 00:43:58.460
And in fact, if they
weren't accompanied by a man,

00:43:58.460 --> 00:44:01.220
they were often sent back
for a lot of reasons.

00:44:01.220 --> 00:44:04.000
And the third thing is
that it didn't really work,

00:44:04.000 --> 00:44:07.570
because most immigrants who
were coming were literate,

00:44:07.570 --> 00:44:10.520
even though some were from
southern and eastern Europe.

00:44:10.520 --> 00:44:13.660
Here is a part two.

00:44:13.660 --> 00:44:19.440
The literacy test, it's actually
against the literacy test.

00:44:19.440 --> 00:44:22.690
The American east -- and this
is what the caption reads.

00:44:22.690 --> 00:44:26.160
"The American east wall
as Congressman Burnett,"

00:44:26.160 --> 00:44:28.290
one of the supporters,
"would build it."

00:44:28.290 --> 00:44:33.200
Interesting that it's a
wall to keep -- you know.

00:44:33.200 --> 00:44:35.900
And this is the 1890's.

00:44:35.900 --> 00:44:38.410
To keep people out.

00:44:38.410 --> 00:44:42.480
The pens are weapons
pointing out.

00:44:42.480 --> 00:44:45.070
And the roof of the
wall are books.

00:44:45.070 --> 00:44:51.200
It is true that immigrants had
entered into the United States

00:44:51.200 --> 00:44:54.150
in more or less unrestricted
numbers.

00:44:54.150 --> 00:44:56.890
Between 1905 and
1914, for example,

00:44:56.890 --> 00:45:00.510
almost 9.9 million
European immigrants had come

00:45:00.510 --> 00:45:04.230
to the United States, most from
southern and eastern Europe.

00:45:04.230 --> 00:45:07.190
So Congress sought to establish
a quota system limiting

00:45:07.190 --> 00:45:09.310
immigration by country.

00:45:09.310 --> 00:45:12.930
In 1921, it passed the
Emergency Immigration Act,

00:45:12.930 --> 00:45:14.340
setting the total
number of immigrants

00:45:14.340 --> 00:45:17.920
from all countries
at 355,000 a year.

00:45:17.920 --> 00:45:20.320
And basing each country's
allotment

00:45:20.320 --> 00:45:23.310
on a complicated formula which
reflected how many immigrants

00:45:23.310 --> 00:45:26.210
of that country had
lived here in 1910.

00:45:26.210 --> 00:45:29.840
Okay. Nativists still
thought the quotas for eastern

00:45:29.840 --> 00:45:35.400
and southern Europeans
were too high.

00:45:35.400 --> 00:45:38.440
They feared that jobs would
be taken away from Americans,

00:45:38.440 --> 00:45:41.040
that communists, labor
agitators, other radicals

00:45:41.040 --> 00:45:43.780
and criminals would
enter the United States

00:45:43.780 --> 00:45:46.700
and too many immigrants
could not be assimilated

00:45:46.700 --> 00:45:49.900
and would change the
character of the country.

00:45:49.900 --> 00:45:52.570
This is a quote, "The old
Americans are getting a little

00:45:52.570 --> 00:45:54.170
panicky and no wonder.

00:45:54.170 --> 00:45:55.670
America, Americans

00:45:55.670 --> 00:45:58.590
and Americanism are being
crowded out of America."

00:45:58.590 --> 00:46:03.650
And this was from a reader to
the New Republican in 1924.

00:46:03.650 --> 00:46:05.640
Now Albert Johnson,
a congressman

00:46:05.640 --> 00:46:09.290
from Washington State, led
the fight for tougher quotas.

00:46:09.290 --> 00:46:14.930
He said -- the quote above
is part of what he said.

00:46:14.930 --> 00:46:19.000
He said, "Today, instead of a
well-knit homogenous citizenry,

00:46:19.000 --> 00:46:21.630
we have a body politic
made up of all

00:46:21.630 --> 00:46:23.430
and every diverse element.

00:46:23.430 --> 00:46:27.100
Our capacity to maintain our
cherished institutions stands

00:46:27.100 --> 00:46:31.880
diluted by a stream
of alien blood.

00:46:31.880 --> 00:46:35.150
It is no wonder,"
remember, this is talking

00:46:35.150 --> 00:46:38.330
about Italian Americans,
"therefore that the myth

00:46:38.330 --> 00:46:40.850
of the melting pot
has been discredited.

00:46:40.850 --> 00:46:43.490
The day of [inaudible]
welcome to all peoples,

00:46:43.490 --> 00:46:45.210
the day of indiscriminate
acceptance

00:46:45.210 --> 00:46:47.750
of all races has
definitely ended."

00:46:47.750 --> 00:46:51.740
When Congress passed the
Johnson-Reed Act in 1924,

00:46:51.740 --> 00:46:56.080
it used the 1890 census for
the basis of quota elevations

00:46:56.080 --> 00:46:58.290
because in 1890 there
had been more northern

00:46:58.290 --> 00:47:00.430
and western European
immigrants and fewer southern

00:47:00.430 --> 00:47:03.980
and eastern European immigrants
living in the United States.

00:47:03.980 --> 00:47:06.840
Congress and much of the
country wanted the United States

00:47:06.840 --> 00:47:09.240
to return to its English roots.

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:13.710
And that meant having immigrants
from Britain or western

00:47:13.710 --> 00:47:17.140
and northern Europeans
be recorded in the census

00:47:17.140 --> 00:47:19.620
as the largest group
in the population.

00:47:19.620 --> 00:47:21.940
Okay, the total number
of immigrants

00:47:21.940 --> 00:47:23.970
from every country
was drastically cut

00:47:23.970 --> 00:47:29.400
to 150,000 per year
with this quota act.

00:47:29.400 --> 00:47:32.370
The yearly quota for the United
Kingdom, which is England,

00:47:32.370 --> 00:47:38.370
Wales, Scotland and
Northern Ireland, was 65,721.

00:47:38.370 --> 00:47:41.570
After he 1920's,
the yearly quota

00:47:41.570 --> 00:47:47.010
for Italians was 5,802 a year.

00:47:47.010 --> 00:47:49.590
Now Father Ezio is going to
talk to you about the internment

00:47:49.590 --> 00:47:52.230
of Italians during World War II.

00:47:52.230 --> 00:47:57.690
But let me skip past that
just to say two things.

00:47:57.690 --> 00:47:59.680
One is that Italian
Americans served

00:47:59.680 --> 00:48:02.130
in great numbers
in World War II.

00:48:02.130 --> 00:48:06.380
They had become Americans,
very patriotic Americans.

00:48:06.380 --> 00:48:11.720
And this picture shows women at
a flat-raising ceremony in 1942.

00:48:11.720 --> 00:48:16.540
As for the quota
system, in 1952,

00:48:16.540 --> 00:48:19.370
the McCarron-Walter Act
changed the way quota numbers

00:48:19.370 --> 00:48:20.670
were figured.

00:48:20.670 --> 00:48:22.040
And I know the details
can be boring,

00:48:22.040 --> 00:48:27.700
but the important thing was
it kept the country quotas.

00:48:27.700 --> 00:48:29.950
And McCarron said, "We have

00:48:29.950 --> 00:48:33.310
in the United States today
hardcore, indigestible blocks

00:48:33.310 --> 00:48:36.580
which have not become integrated
into the American way of life

00:48:36.580 --> 00:48:40.420
but which on the contrary
are its deadly enemies.

00:48:40.420 --> 00:48:44.930
Today, as never before, untold
millions are storming our gates

00:48:44.930 --> 00:48:48.250
for admission and those gates
are cracking under the strain."

00:48:48.250 --> 00:48:50.980
It wasn't actually until 1965

00:48:50.980 --> 00:48:52.910
that Congress passed
the Hart-Seller Act,

00:48:52.910 --> 00:48:55.190
and that eliminated
all national quotas

00:48:55.190 --> 00:48:59.180
and it emphasized having
immigrants come here based

00:48:59.180 --> 00:49:01.790
on family connections
to those already here

00:49:01.790 --> 00:49:03.860
and having special skills.

00:49:03.860 --> 00:49:07.460
Okay. Finally, this
last picture is

00:49:07.460 --> 00:49:11.330
of Lilian Claire,
my first grandchild.

00:49:11.330 --> 00:49:13.510
And this is an opportunity
to show her

00:49:13.510 --> 00:49:15.030
to a large number of people.

00:49:15.030 --> 00:49:17.040
[ Laughter ]

00:49:17.040 --> 00:49:18.970
She was born this
year on August 9th.

00:49:18.970 --> 00:49:20.300
Now I have a reason though.

00:49:20.300 --> 00:49:23.090
I started with photos of
my great-grandparents.

00:49:23.090 --> 00:49:25.560
Here is their descendant.

00:49:25.560 --> 00:49:27.250
Lily is the sixth generation

00:49:27.250 --> 00:49:30.370
of my family story
in the United States.

00:49:30.370 --> 00:49:35.210
You see, despite the language
that demeaned Italian Americans

00:49:35.210 --> 00:49:37.540
and the discriminatory
obstacles that were put

00:49:37.540 --> 00:49:39.900
in their way, we did assimilate.

00:49:39.900 --> 00:49:41.470
We are Americans.

00:49:41.470 --> 00:49:44.710
I hope you will keep in mind the
experiences of Italian Americans

00:49:44.710 --> 00:49:46.910
when thinking about
immigration today.

00:49:46.910 --> 00:49:49.510
Thank you.

00:49:49.510 --> 00:50:00.040
