&gt;&gt; Constance Morella:
The magic touch.

00:50:18.500 --> 00:50:20.740
Thank you very much, Linda.

00:50:20.740 --> 00:50:25.730
I learned a lot from that too,
from the photographs, visually

00:50:25.730 --> 00:50:29.830
and verbally, hearing about
and seeing your grandchild too.

00:50:29.830 --> 00:50:32.700
Isn't it scary when you think

00:50:32.700 --> 00:50:36.160
about how history is repeating
itself, when she talked

00:50:36.160 --> 00:50:42.020
about stereotyping immigration,
the wall, America for Americans?

00:50:42.020 --> 00:50:44.820
So we have a task ahead of us.

00:50:44.820 --> 00:50:46.910
And so I now have
the great pleasure

00:50:46.910 --> 00:50:50.140
of introducing our
second guest speaker.

00:50:50.140 --> 00:50:56.070
And he is somebody that we
have been looking forward

00:50:56.070 --> 00:51:04.180
to hearing from,
Padre Ezio Marchetto.

00:51:04.180 --> 00:51:07.170
He has been, as you know --

00:51:07.170 --> 00:51:09.710
he's been the pastor
of Holy Rosary Church

00:51:09.710 --> 00:51:12.040
for the last five years.

00:51:12.040 --> 00:51:16.290
And not only that, he's
taken on the arduous task

00:51:16.290 --> 00:51:18.840
of a tremendous production

00:51:18.840 --> 00:51:22.680
that is taking place
around Casa Italiana.

00:51:22.680 --> 00:51:25.120
As a matter of fact,
I think in addition

00:51:25.120 --> 00:51:26.940
to his spiritual
responsibilities,

00:51:26.940 --> 00:51:33.090
he chairs the Board of Casa
Italiana Sociocultural Center,

00:51:33.090 --> 00:51:34.390
which is now involved

00:51:34.390 --> 00:51:39.180
in large-scale redevelopment
in this area.

00:51:39.180 --> 00:51:43.830
Incidentally, it is going to
also include the establishment

00:51:43.830 --> 00:51:46.440
of an Italian American museum.

00:51:46.440 --> 00:51:49.200
From what I understand
from Father Ezio,

00:51:49.200 --> 00:51:52.020
it's going to be basically
Italian Americanism

00:51:52.020 --> 00:51:53.900
in the greater Washington area.

00:51:53.900 --> 00:51:57.180
So it will have a specificity

00:51:57.180 --> 00:52:02.200
which will give it even more
pleasure for the viewers.

00:52:02.200 --> 00:52:05.440
Padre Ezio is multilingual.

00:52:05.440 --> 00:52:10.860
He speaks Italian, Portuguese,
English and Canadian English.

00:52:10.860 --> 00:52:12.960
Probably speaks other
languages too.

00:52:12.960 --> 00:52:15.400
You know, I've always
thought when they say

00:52:15.400 --> 00:52:20.250
that you are multilingual, like
he is, you speak many languages.

00:52:20.250 --> 00:52:24.670
And then when you're bilingual,
you speak two languages.

00:52:24.670 --> 00:52:29.510
And when you speak one
language, you're American.

00:52:29.510 --> 00:52:33.090
[ Laughter ]

00:52:33.090 --> 00:52:36.040
But he's multilingual.

00:52:36.040 --> 00:52:37.970
He has of course as you know --

00:52:37.970 --> 00:52:40.710
he studied in Italy,
Portugal and Canada.

00:52:40.710 --> 00:52:44.220
And he's a man who really
understand the media and how

00:52:44.220 --> 00:52:46.090
to get a message across.

00:52:46.090 --> 00:52:49.380
He's a good communicator,
and that's very important.

00:52:49.380 --> 00:52:52.920
His experiences in
speaking, writing,

00:52:52.920 --> 00:52:56.760
participating have
certainly enhanced that.

00:52:56.760 --> 00:53:02.630
Well, I think particularly
pertinent today is his expertise

00:53:02.630 --> 00:53:05.250
on global immigration.

00:53:05.250 --> 00:53:07.220
Global immigration.

00:53:07.220 --> 00:53:10.950
He served as an official
observer at the United Nations

00:53:10.950 --> 00:53:15.700
on the issues of international
migration, something certainly

00:53:15.700 --> 00:53:17.270
that we care about now.

00:53:17.270 --> 00:53:23.510
So it's my honor and pleasure to
present Father Ezio Marchetto.

00:53:23.510 --> 00:53:45.590
[ Applause ]

00:53:45.590 --> 00:53:46.890
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto:
Good evening, everyone.

00:53:46.890 --> 00:53:51.910
Thank you for the organizers
and all of you for being here.

00:53:53.120 --> 00:53:57.730
Let me start by saying what
my presentation is not.

00:53:57.730 --> 00:54:02.590
It's not an exhaustive
presentation on the internment

00:54:02.590 --> 00:54:04.800
of Italian Americans,
for two reasons.

00:54:04.800 --> 00:54:08.920
First, very little
material is available.

00:54:08.920 --> 00:54:11.400
For those who are
interested, I have a page

00:54:11.400 --> 00:54:14.230
and that's all the
resources that we have

00:54:14.230 --> 00:54:18.530
about the internment
of Italian Americans.

00:54:18.530 --> 00:54:22.030
The user entry of
Wikipedia, about three books,

00:54:22.030 --> 00:54:29.560
a few articles, one video
and one fiction book.

00:54:29.560 --> 00:54:31.860
That's all.

00:54:35.320 --> 00:54:37.760
So there is another
element which is many

00:54:37.760 --> 00:54:42.100
of the information are a little
confusing for this reason.

00:54:42.100 --> 00:54:46.350
As you will see later on on
the numbers, one camp says

00:54:46.350 --> 00:54:51.280
that Italian American
internees were 250.

00:54:51.280 --> 00:54:54.110
Another one says
they were over 1,000.

00:54:54.110 --> 00:54:56.880
The reason is these
are a chapter

00:54:56.880 --> 00:55:00.830
of Italian American history
which seems to be forgotten.

00:55:00.830 --> 00:55:08.490
How many of you know that 55,000
Italian POW's were brought

00:55:08.490 --> 00:55:14.380
to the United States
during World War II?

00:55:14.380 --> 00:55:16.040
Thank you.

00:55:16.040 --> 00:55:21.540
55,000. That seems to be
one of those just forgotten,

00:55:21.540 --> 00:55:23.780
"Let's not talk about
it" situations.

00:55:23.780 --> 00:55:27.010
But let's start with
our topic tonight.

00:55:27.010 --> 00:55:30.580
The title For Memory
[inaudible] is taken

00:55:30.580 --> 00:55:34.420
from the diary of
Prospero Chaconi.

00:55:34.420 --> 00:55:37.910
That's the first
page of his book.

00:55:37.910 --> 00:55:42.980
It recalls all the different
moments of his truly statements

00:55:42.980 --> 00:55:47.320
of the cross, the painful
journey through internment.

00:55:47.320 --> 00:55:52.060
Let's just start with
some basic facts.

00:55:52.060 --> 00:55:56.010
Fact one, between 1876 and 1930,

00:55:56.010 --> 00:56:00.430
5 million Italians moved
to the United States.

00:56:00.430 --> 00:56:02.290
5 millions.

00:56:02.290 --> 00:56:09.620
Fact two, in 1942,
beginning with the war,

00:56:09.620 --> 00:56:18.720
there were 695,000 Italian
citizens present n the

00:56:18.720 --> 00:56:21.020
United States.

00:56:22.620 --> 00:56:27.680
Three, during World War II,
more than half a million --

00:56:27.680 --> 00:56:32.060
some numbers go up
to 1.5 million,

00:56:32.060 --> 00:56:35.800
but there's not a
complete list --

00:56:35.800 --> 00:56:40.500
but over half a million Italian
Americans were in the Army.

00:56:40.500 --> 00:56:42.750
Now remember, the whole
army was about 12 million.

00:56:42.750 --> 00:56:48.650
So about half a million and over
was quite a remarkable number.

00:56:49.870 --> 00:56:51.650
Number four, during the war,

00:56:51.650 --> 00:56:55.330
no person of Italian descent
was ever charged with,

00:56:55.330 --> 00:56:59.510
much less convicted
of, espionage, sabotage

00:56:59.510 --> 00:57:01.870
or any other hostile action.

00:57:01.870 --> 00:57:04.960
These are facts.

00:57:04.960 --> 00:57:12.020
Finally, fact one, the
executive order 9066 called

00:57:12.020 --> 00:57:14.460
for compulsory relocation
of more

00:57:14.460 --> 00:57:18.980
than 10,000 Italian Americans.

00:57:18.980 --> 00:57:23.030
And at the same time,
restricted movement of more

00:57:23.030 --> 00:57:27.210
than 600,000 Italian
Americans nationwide.

00:57:27.210 --> 00:57:32.670
So let's take a look now at what
happened, how they went there.

00:57:32.670 --> 00:57:36.580
In the beginning, there was a
lot of admiration for Mussolini.

00:57:36.580 --> 00:57:40.230
Here we have two
quotes from Roosevelt.

00:57:40.230 --> 00:57:42.980
"I am interested
and deeply impressed

00:57:42.980 --> 00:57:47.990
by what he has accomplished by
his evidenced, honest purpose

00:57:47.990 --> 00:57:50.160
in restoring Italy and seeking

00:57:50.160 --> 00:57:53.040
to prevent general
European trouble."

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:56.550
He made the covers
of Newsweek and Time.

00:57:56.550 --> 00:58:01.200
A few weeks later, "I don't
mind telling you in confidence,

00:58:01.200 --> 00:58:04.810
I am keeping in fairly
close touch

00:58:04.810 --> 00:58:08.460
with the admirable
Italian gentleman."

00:58:10.510 --> 00:58:13.920
[ Laughter ]

00:58:13.920 --> 00:58:17.920
It was a time when Italian
Americans start to succeed,

00:58:17.920 --> 00:58:20.840
to be recognized,
to reach the level

00:58:20.840 --> 00:58:24.590
when a community
becomes noticeable.

00:58:24.590 --> 00:58:31.160
And as always, politics is a
great indicator of the position

00:58:31.160 --> 00:58:34.220
in society of a specific
ethnic group.

00:58:34.220 --> 00:58:37.570
It was a time when
Congressman Feralo Laguardia,

00:58:37.570 --> 00:58:42.280
Victor Mark Antonio, Mayor
Frank Orizio, Joseph Felioto,

00:58:42.280 --> 00:58:46.300
[inaudible] Marciano,
Jody Margo --

00:58:46.300 --> 00:58:49.220
this was the time
when they start to be

00:58:49.220 --> 00:58:53.090
in the news in a positive way.

00:58:56.040 --> 00:58:59.440
At the same time, trouble
was brewing in Europe.

00:58:59.440 --> 00:59:03.860
Roma-Berlin Axis became a
military alliance in 1939.

00:59:03.860 --> 00:59:07.520
Their pact was sealed and
they were the three powers,

00:59:07.520 --> 00:59:10.810
Germany, Italy, Japan.

00:59:10.810 --> 00:59:19.230
War. A date which will live
in infamy, December 7th, 1941.

00:59:19.230 --> 00:59:21.890
And that's when everything
fell apart.

00:59:21.890 --> 00:59:28.680
What is interesting is that
on the night of December 7th,

00:59:28.680 --> 00:59:30.430
right after Pearl Harbor,

00:59:30.430 --> 00:59:36.830
and before US declared
officially war to Italy,

00:59:36.830 --> 00:59:39.910
the FBI arrested a
handful of Italians.

00:59:39.910 --> 00:59:42.570
You see the map, and
you see the date.

00:59:42.570 --> 00:59:45.070
The Sanborn Nine.

00:59:46.470 --> 00:59:53.950
They had a list of
suspected dangerous aliens.

00:59:58.040 --> 01:00:00.550
December 11th, the
official declaration of war,

01:00:00.550 --> 01:00:03.260
Germany declared war
on the United States

01:00:03.260 --> 01:00:09.710
and immediately the US president
Roosevelt announced America was

01:00:09.710 --> 01:00:14.260
at war with Japan
and the alliance.

01:00:14.260 --> 01:00:18.720
So Italian dictator Benito
Mussolini made this declaration

01:00:18.720 --> 01:00:20.020
from [inaudible] Rome,

01:00:20.020 --> 01:00:26.040
the powers of the pact
were determined to win.

01:00:26.040 --> 01:00:29.560
And of course we have
the message of Congress,

01:00:29.560 --> 01:00:31.420
requesting a recognition
of state of war

01:00:31.420 --> 01:00:33.540
with Germany and Italy.

01:00:33.540 --> 01:00:37.230
There had never been a greater
challenge to life, liberty,

01:00:37.230 --> 01:00:40.870
civilization than that
created by the Axis Powers,

01:00:40.870 --> 01:00:42.700
Germany, Italy and Japan.

01:00:42.700 --> 01:00:47.380
It was determined therefore
to have the forces of justice

01:00:47.380 --> 01:00:50.410
and righteousness
prevail over the forces

01:00:50.410 --> 01:00:53.900
of savagery and barbarism.

01:00:53.900 --> 01:00:58.420
So all of a sudden, all the
immigrants from Germany,

01:00:58.420 --> 01:01:03.990
Italy and Japan found themselves
as at war with their homeland.

01:01:08.050 --> 01:01:09.350
Again, as I mentioned before,

01:01:09.350 --> 01:01:12.490
the enemy aliens were
taken into custody.

01:01:12.490 --> 01:01:17.880
Less than two weeks later,
General DeWitt commanded

01:01:17.880 --> 01:01:20.570
that all aliens under 14 years

01:01:20.570 --> 01:01:23.450
of age be removed
to the interior.

01:01:23.450 --> 01:01:27.190
This had a great effect
especially in California.

01:01:27.190 --> 01:01:28.550
They were expecting Japan

01:01:28.550 --> 01:01:32.480
to attack the United
States from the west coast.

01:01:32.480 --> 01:01:38.560
So they insisted to move
inland all the enemy aliens.

01:01:38.560 --> 01:01:44.870
Then in 1942 the status of enemy
alien was extended to all aliens

01:01:44.870 --> 01:01:50.460
of Italian descent,
which is over 600,000.

01:01:50.460 --> 01:01:54.840
These individuals were
required to register

01:01:54.840 --> 01:01:58.470
and reregister to
the post office.

01:01:58.470 --> 01:02:03.510
There are four dates that
are the turning points.

01:02:03.510 --> 01:02:06.960
Of course, December
7th, 1941, Pearl Harbor.

01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:09.910
January 25th, 1942, immediately

01:02:09.910 --> 01:02:14.210
after Pearl Harbor the
Rabas Commission was trying

01:02:14.210 --> 01:02:16.710
to figure out what went wrong.

01:02:16.710 --> 01:02:18.010
And some of the suggestions

01:02:18.010 --> 01:02:20.980
that came back were
there were fifth columns

01:02:20.980 --> 01:02:22.780
within the United States.

01:02:22.780 --> 01:02:30.790
And January 29th, 1942, we have
the first enemy alien relocation

01:02:30.790 --> 01:02:32.090
that was issued.

01:02:32.090 --> 01:02:37.660
Then the executive order 9066.

01:02:37.660 --> 01:02:42.890
So all people were excluded
from specific areas.

01:02:42.890 --> 01:02:46.090
This is the notice
to alien enemies.

01:02:46.090 --> 01:02:53.610
About 4 million aliens,
which means citizens

01:02:53.610 --> 01:02:58.240
who kept their Italian,
Japanese or German citizenship.

01:02:58.240 --> 01:03:01.600
So after Pearl Harbor --

01:03:01.600 --> 01:03:05.290
I'm sorry, those were the
immigrants at the time.

01:03:05.290 --> 01:03:09.460
About 1.1 million of these
immigrants were still citizens

01:03:09.460 --> 01:03:10.880
of Germany, Italy and Japan

01:03:10.880 --> 01:03:16.160
and automatically
became enemy aliens.

01:03:16.160 --> 01:03:19.150
And that's the notice that
went around the country,

01:03:19.150 --> 01:03:24.650
both in English, Japanese,
Italian and German,

01:03:24.650 --> 01:03:30.580
telling them they must register
and move out of specific areas.

01:03:30.580 --> 01:03:34.820
So here we have about 122,000
men and women and children

01:03:34.820 --> 01:03:38.630
of Japanese ancestry were
evicted from the west coast

01:03:38.630 --> 01:03:43.040
of the United States and held
in American concentration camps,

01:03:43.040 --> 01:03:46.420
the internment camps
if you want.

01:03:46.420 --> 01:03:47.720
Americans with Italian

01:03:47.720 --> 01:03:50.760
and German ancestry were also
targeted by these restrictions,

01:03:50.760 --> 01:03:55.460
including internment of 11,000
people of German ancestry,

01:03:55.460 --> 01:03:59.110
and about 3,000 people
with Italian ancestry.

01:03:59.110 --> 01:04:02.450
Along with some Jewish refugees,

01:04:02.450 --> 01:04:05.430
because they were
coming from Germany.

01:04:09.040 --> 01:04:11.080
The major internment sites for
Italian Americans were Port

01:04:11.080 --> 01:04:16.580
of George, Maryland; [inaudible]
in Oklahoma for some years,

01:04:16.580 --> 01:04:20.650
in Texas and Tennessee.

01:04:20.650 --> 01:04:25.670
The largest number were
at Fort Visola in Montana.

01:04:25.670 --> 01:04:27.940
And here's where the
numbers get confused.

01:04:27.940 --> 01:04:29.530
Because a large number

01:04:29.530 --> 01:04:33.320
of the Italian POW's
were also at that camp.

01:04:33.320 --> 01:04:38.230
So the numbers go from, you
will see later one of the signs

01:04:38.230 --> 01:04:42.480
that there were over 1,000
Italian Americans interned,

01:04:42.480 --> 01:04:44.220
but that's not really true.

01:04:44.220 --> 01:04:50.330
It was the mixing of Italian
POW's and Italian Americans.

01:04:50.330 --> 01:04:52.510
So --

01:04:52.510 --> 01:05:19.070
[ Speaking Italian ]

01:05:19.070 --> 01:05:22.280
You have the three languages,
Japanese, Italian and German.

01:05:22.280 --> 01:05:29.530
This is a copy of
one of those cards.

01:05:29.530 --> 01:05:33.950
What was also very sad is this:

01:05:33.950 --> 01:05:39.850
besides to carry all the time
your identification card,

01:05:39.850 --> 01:05:42.050
there were travel restrictions.

01:05:42.050 --> 01:05:45.210
You cannot travel
more than five miles.

01:05:45.210 --> 01:05:49.340
They were required to hand
over all the contraband,

01:05:49.340 --> 01:05:53.640
which means cameras, weapons,
flashlights that can be used

01:05:53.640 --> 01:05:58.490
to signal across the ocean.

01:05:58.490 --> 01:06:00.970
[ Laughter ]

01:06:00.970 --> 01:06:02.270
And short-wave radios.

01:06:02.270 --> 01:06:04.700
This was a very sad time.

01:06:04.700 --> 01:06:07.270
There was an instance
on the west coast,

01:06:07.270 --> 01:06:10.600
a number of people
committed suicide.

01:06:10.600 --> 01:06:13.090
One man went to the barn

01:06:13.090 --> 01:06:16.590
and asked his friend
to please shoot him.

01:06:16.590 --> 01:06:18.910
Because his friend
refused, he walked out

01:06:18.910 --> 01:06:22.220
and threw himself under a train.

01:06:22.220 --> 01:06:26.040
Because he had his family
there and grew up there,

01:06:26.040 --> 01:06:28.200
he felt he was American.

01:06:28.200 --> 01:06:30.500
He felt betrayed.

01:06:34.040 --> 01:06:36.330
All the Italian schools
were closed,

01:06:36.330 --> 01:06:38.960
Italian American
meetings became suspected.

01:06:38.960 --> 01:06:44.610
The American organizations and
social clubs were [inaudible],

01:06:44.610 --> 01:06:46.040
and this is one of the posters.

01:06:46.040 --> 01:06:48.070
[ Speaking Italian ]

01:06:48.070 --> 01:06:51.970
I don't read Japanese or German,
but that's what the message was.

01:06:51.970 --> 01:06:54.520
Don't speak the enemy language.

01:06:59.040 --> 01:07:02.150
Ultimately, about 600,000
Americans were arrested.

01:07:02.150 --> 01:07:04.810
250,000 were interned.

01:07:04.810 --> 01:07:07.390
Once you are arrested, you
have the right to go in front

01:07:07.390 --> 01:07:10.390
of a panel that will judge
if you were considered

01:07:10.390 --> 01:07:12.310
to be a danger or not.

01:07:12.310 --> 01:07:14.760
You still have to carry
your identification,

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:17.240
travel restrictions.

01:07:17.240 --> 01:07:26.790
Also, you have to remember this:
enemy alien prohibited areas.

01:07:26.790 --> 01:07:28.600
The fact that you could not go

01:07:28.600 --> 01:07:32.820
into certain areas
means you lost your job.

01:07:32.820 --> 01:07:38.030
Your business was either you
have to close it or walk away.

01:07:38.030 --> 01:07:40.420
You were enemy aliens.

01:07:41.770 --> 01:07:45.490
Thousands of people
lost everything.

01:07:45.490 --> 01:07:50.480
That was very sad.

01:07:50.480 --> 01:07:54.640
Rosina Trovato was
classified enemy alien.

01:07:54.640 --> 01:07:58.540
She was to move out
of a specific area,

01:07:58.540 --> 01:08:02.640
and she received a notice
to evacuate, and she learned

01:08:02.640 --> 01:08:07.140
that her son has gone down
with the US [inaudible].

01:08:11.040 --> 01:08:14.770
Jody Mago, his father
could not go

01:08:14.770 --> 01:08:18.070
down to visit his
son's restaurant

01:08:18.070 --> 01:08:22.200
because it was outside the
area he was allowed to travel.

01:08:22.200 --> 01:08:29.630
[Inaudible] that 52,000 Italian
aliens cannot leave their homes

01:08:29.630 --> 01:08:33.250
between 8:00 PM and 5:00 AM.

01:08:33.250 --> 01:08:38.270
So all those who
work in bakeries,

01:08:38.270 --> 01:08:41.820
they just lost their job.

01:08:45.040 --> 01:08:48.040
There were about 1,400
Italian American fishermen

01:08:48.040 --> 01:08:53.410
in San Francisco and
again, they cannot set foot

01:08:53.410 --> 01:08:58.430
on their waterfront after
February 24th, 1942.

01:08:58.430 --> 01:09:04.260
And this was the crazy part: the
fishing industry was considered

01:09:04.260 --> 01:09:09.080
to be a national priority.

01:09:09.080 --> 01:09:13.200
Seafood was providing
food for the nation.

01:09:13.200 --> 01:09:15.580
And here we have 90%

01:09:15.580 --> 01:09:21.760
of San Francisco being either
sequestered by the Coast Guard

01:09:21.760 --> 01:09:26.340
or left idle because people
cannot access the waterfront.

01:09:26.340 --> 01:09:31.410
Even one of the newspapers
said, "Fishermen with 23 sons

01:09:31.410 --> 01:09:37.120
in the Army and Navy are bound
to wharf while boat lies idle,

01:09:37.120 --> 01:09:39.470
and the seafood is needed."

01:09:39.470 --> 01:09:42.100
I mean, it was so evident.

01:09:42.100 --> 01:09:48.400
Yet months would pass before
the restrictions were rescinded.

01:09:48.400 --> 01:09:52.680
This is just one example
of how confusion happens.

01:09:52.680 --> 01:10:00.790
From 1841-44, [inaudible] as
a detention center for more

01:10:00.790 --> 01:10:04.450
than 1,000 Italians,
more than 1,000 Japanese

01:10:04.450 --> 01:10:07.110
and 22 German nationalists.

01:10:07.110 --> 01:10:11.130
The Italians were the fair
workers and civilian seamen,

01:10:11.130 --> 01:10:16.220
who were bounded at the outbreak
of the war against the Japanese.

01:10:17.420 --> 01:10:23.540
So about 250 Italian Americans
were put in internment camps,

01:10:23.540 --> 01:10:28.500
but the biggest was the
curfew and the restrictions.

01:10:28.500 --> 01:10:36.610
Then they started to realize
the Italians were not really

01:10:36.610 --> 01:10:38.680
so great enemies.

01:10:38.680 --> 01:10:42.150
And the reason was so many
families had their sons

01:10:42.150 --> 01:10:43.530
in the Army.

01:10:43.530 --> 01:10:49.060
Over a million, or as some
numbers put it, over a million.

01:10:49.060 --> 01:10:51.470
So try to backtrack.

01:10:51.470 --> 01:10:56.160
And in July 1942,
President Roosevelt started

01:10:56.160 --> 01:10:59.520
to consider some
form of restitution,

01:10:59.520 --> 01:11:02.320
the lifting of restrictions.

01:11:02.320 --> 01:11:03.730
And they even said, "Well,

01:11:03.730 --> 01:11:08.960
we're going to pay you $20
unemployment for each week

01:11:08.960 --> 01:11:11.320
that you were out of your job."

01:11:11.320 --> 01:11:15.010
Of the more than 2,500
Italian American detainees,

01:11:15.010 --> 01:11:17.240
about 300 took the offer.

01:11:17.240 --> 01:11:20.460
For them it was a
slap in the face.

01:11:20.460 --> 01:11:26.860
So on Columbus Day,
October 12th, 1942,

01:11:26.860 --> 01:11:32.870
the attorney general Francis
Biddell, here with Laguardia

01:11:32.870 --> 01:11:35.670
in New York, signed
the document.

01:11:35.670 --> 01:11:40.430
The Italian nationals in the
US will no longer be classified

01:11:40.430 --> 01:11:42.680
as enemies.

01:11:42.680 --> 01:11:50.450
It was just a move to help
support the war effort.

01:11:50.450 --> 01:11:53.710
Then we have this, Mr.
Speaker arrives today

01:11:53.710 --> 01:11:57.270
to introduce a bill that will
cause the president on behalf

01:11:57.270 --> 01:12:00.490
of the United States government
to formally acknowledge

01:12:00.490 --> 01:12:02.000
that the civil liberties

01:12:02.000 --> 01:12:06.380
of Italian Americans were
violated during World War II.

01:12:06.380 --> 01:12:11.490
Congressman Rick Lasio and Eliot
Angle together introduce this.

01:12:11.490 --> 01:12:20.070
So it finally became a
public law number 106-451.

01:12:20.070 --> 01:12:23.060
It passed the Congress, 1997.

01:12:23.060 --> 01:12:28.550
And these are what the
commission that was formed

01:12:28.550 --> 01:12:33.630
with that law tried to achieve.

01:12:33.630 --> 01:12:37.540
One, to formally acknowledge
the violation of civil liberties

01:12:37.540 --> 01:12:40.130
of Italian Americans
in World War II.

01:12:40.130 --> 01:12:44.960
Two, to encourage a federal
agency to support projects

01:12:44.960 --> 01:12:46.980
that will heighten
public awareness

01:12:46.980 --> 01:12:49.390
of this forgotten episode.

01:12:49.390 --> 01:12:52.680
Three, to provide
direct national support

01:12:52.680 --> 01:12:55.670
for a documentary film.

01:12:55.670 --> 01:12:58.210
Four, formation of
advisory committee

01:12:58.210 --> 01:12:59.510
to assist the collection

01:12:59.510 --> 01:13:02.110
of relevant information
regarding the matter

01:13:02.110 --> 01:13:05.000
as it relates to
public policy matters.

01:13:05.000 --> 01:13:08.070
Finally, to publish a
report regarding the role

01:13:08.070 --> 01:13:10.050
of the government
of the United States

01:13:10.050 --> 01:13:12.780
on this unfortunate occurrence.

01:13:12.780 --> 01:13:17.940
It was passed in the
year 2000, October 24th

01:13:17.940 --> 01:13:20.020
with the Senate's amendments.

01:13:20.020 --> 01:13:24.640
So on November 7th, 2000,

01:13:24.640 --> 01:13:28.030
the US Congress passed
the Wartime Violation

01:13:28.030 --> 01:13:30.640
of Italian American
Civil Liberties Act,

01:13:30.640 --> 01:13:37.300
and those are the
groups that came

01:13:37.300 --> 01:13:43.490
into this US Congress statement.

01:13:49.220 --> 01:13:52.860
Why isn't this such
an easy topic

01:13:52.860 --> 01:13:55.210
in Italian American history?

01:13:55.210 --> 01:14:02.280
I'm not a psychologist,
but I believe the reason is

01:14:02.280 --> 01:14:07.650
for Italian Americans, there
was some kind of mixed feeling.

01:14:07.650 --> 01:14:10.950
In one sense they felt
betrayed, especially those

01:14:10.950 --> 01:14:14.450
who were detained, or those
who had their boats confiscated

01:14:14.450 --> 01:14:16.240
or they lost their jobs,

01:14:16.240 --> 01:14:21.970
families that were separated
while their sons were at war.

01:14:21.970 --> 01:14:24.840
At the same time, they
were still living here.

01:14:24.840 --> 01:14:27.390
They wanted to be
Italian Americans.

01:14:27.390 --> 01:14:29.460
They wanted to be Americans.

01:14:29.460 --> 01:14:32.230
So for many of the
older people, they said,

01:14:32.230 --> 01:14:33.530
"Let's not talk about it.

01:14:33.530 --> 01:14:34.830
The past is gone.

01:14:34.830 --> 01:14:36.580
Italy was at war.

01:14:36.580 --> 01:14:39.240
They are not saying
it was our fault."

01:14:39.240 --> 01:14:40.830
But they have mixed feelings.

01:14:40.830 --> 01:14:43.030
Guilty in one sense
because Italy declared war

01:14:43.030 --> 01:14:46.020
on the United States,
betrayal in the other

01:14:46.020 --> 01:14:51.710
because they felt not recognized
for who they truly were.

01:14:51.710 --> 01:14:58.570
Not one single person was
ever convicted or accused

01:14:58.570 --> 01:15:03.700
of any anti-American action.

01:15:03.700 --> 01:15:09.350
So it was one of those
things that is gone, is past;

01:15:09.350 --> 01:15:11.610
let's not talk about it.

01:15:11.610 --> 01:15:14.000
But personally, I
believe it's part

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:16.490
of our Italian American history.

01:15:16.490 --> 01:15:20.410
So I hope tonight not to
give you all the answers,

01:15:20.410 --> 01:15:23.870
but just to awaken
your curiosity.

01:15:23.870 --> 01:15:26.580
And these copies
of the bibliography

01:15:26.580 --> 01:15:28.970
or the resources are available.

01:15:28.970 --> 01:15:31.630
It will be a great topic
for any dissertation

01:15:31.630 --> 01:15:35.080
that I hope one day someone
will take the time to do.

01:15:35.080 --> 01:15:36.430
Thank you very much.

01:15:36.430 --> 01:15:38.510
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Thank you.

01:15:38.510 --> 01:15:44.040
[ Applause ]

01:15:44.040 --> 01:15:46.160
I think it's a very
good point, Father Ezio,

01:15:46.160 --> 01:15:48.630
that somebody could
take this topic on

01:15:48.630 --> 01:15:51.000
and do all kinds
of things with it.

01:15:51.000 --> 01:15:57.270
A dissertation, a lengthy
essay; there's so much

01:15:57.270 --> 01:15:59.050
that can be done with it.

01:15:59.050 --> 01:16:04.810
I do want to point
out that in 2010,

01:16:04.810 --> 01:16:11.170
the California legislature
passed a resolution apologizing

01:16:11.170 --> 01:16:14.290
for the United States'
mistreatment

01:16:14.290 --> 01:16:19.720
of Italian residents in
the state during the war.

01:16:19.720 --> 01:16:23.980
Noting restrictions
and indignities as well

01:16:23.980 --> 01:16:26.380
as loss of jobs and housing.

01:16:26.380 --> 01:16:30.080
I guess California because
they were the most affected

01:16:30.080 --> 01:16:33.330
by these indignities
and these crimes.

01:16:33.330 --> 01:16:36.980
And then a member
of Congress now --

01:16:36.980 --> 01:16:41.530
in fact, I served with her --
Zoe Loftgren from California,

01:16:41.530 --> 01:16:43.620
she has presented legislation.

01:16:43.620 --> 01:16:44.920
She couldn't be here tonight

01:16:44.920 --> 01:16:47.600
because of course,
they're campaigning.

01:16:47.600 --> 01:16:50.730
Every two years is ridiculous.

01:16:50.730 --> 01:16:55.120
But the Senate wouldn't change
it to make it four years,

01:16:55.120 --> 01:16:57.160
of course, because
they have six years

01:16:57.160 --> 01:16:59.060
and might have competition.

01:16:59.060 --> 01:17:02.390
But Zoe Loftgren in
the 115th Congress

01:17:02.390 --> 01:17:06.170
which we still have going on
now, introduced two pieces

01:17:06.170 --> 01:17:14.670
of pertinent legislation, and
they are HR-1706 and 1707.

01:17:14.670 --> 01:17:18.010
Pretty reminiscent of
what we had discussed.

01:17:18.010 --> 01:17:22.910
1706 would authorize the
secretary of education

01:17:22.910 --> 01:17:27.500
to provide grants for education
programs on the history

01:17:27.500 --> 01:17:33.330
of the treatment of Italian
Americans during World War II.

01:17:33.330 --> 01:17:41.180
HR-1707 would ask for an
apology for the treatment

01:17:41.180 --> 01:17:45.040
of Italian Americans
during World War II.

01:17:45.040 --> 01:17:46.340
I have copies.

01:17:46.340 --> 01:17:49.270
Her office sent copies
of those two bills

01:17:49.270 --> 01:17:52.120
if anybody would
like to look at them.

01:17:52.120 --> 01:17:55.500
And so now, ladies and
gentlemen, I'd like to open it

01:17:55.500 --> 01:17:57.470
up to questions you may have.

01:17:57.470 --> 01:18:00.290
I think I'd like to
maybe just start off

01:18:00.290 --> 01:18:05.920
and ask our two presenters if
they would like to ask questions

01:18:05.920 --> 01:18:09.770
of each other, or make
any final comments.

01:18:09.770 --> 01:18:12.070
Linda, do you want
to mention anything,

01:18:12.070 --> 01:18:14.430
or wait for the questions?

01:18:14.430 --> 01:18:15.850
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne: Only

01:18:15.850 --> 01:18:19.970
that Italian internment
during World War II is

01:18:19.970 --> 01:18:23.490
in our book, so we
didn't miss it.

01:18:23.490 --> 01:18:25.990
There's a whole page on it.

01:18:25.990 --> 01:18:28.630
And it was not something
that I had any idea

01:18:28.630 --> 01:18:32.870
about until I had
researched this book.

01:18:32.870 --> 01:18:34.170
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella:
Which shows the need

01:18:34.170 --> 01:18:35.470
for a forum like this.

01:18:35.470 --> 01:18:36.770
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne: Yes.

01:18:36.770 --> 01:18:38.740
And I thought your
presentation was wonderful.

01:18:38.740 --> 01:18:40.600
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Any
comments you'd like to make?

01:18:40.600 --> 01:18:41.900
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto: Yeah,
I've been in North America

01:18:41.900 --> 01:18:43.840
for about 30 years,
even though most

01:18:43.840 --> 01:18:45.800
of my time was spent in Canada.

01:18:45.800 --> 01:18:51.010
But it also amazes me how
little history is known.

01:18:51.010 --> 01:18:52.910
A while ago I was talking

01:18:52.910 --> 01:18:56.780
to some people about
Sacrament City.

01:18:56.780 --> 01:18:59.430
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: I
was thinking of them, yeah.

01:18:59.430 --> 01:19:03.420
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto: I
mean, such an integral part

01:19:03.420 --> 01:19:11.030
of so many topics from
unionizing to the freedom,

01:19:11.030 --> 01:19:15.240
but very few people new
about Sacrament City.

01:19:15.240 --> 01:19:23.600
So we have to know more about
how history, all aspects,

01:19:23.600 --> 01:19:26.760
the good ones and the
negative ones, because that's

01:19:26.760 --> 01:19:29.930
in this balance that we
keep growing, learning

01:19:29.930 --> 01:19:33.710
and avoiding hopefully
similar mistakes.

01:19:33.710 --> 01:19:35.010
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Very true.

01:19:35.010 --> 01:19:36.450
Okay, folks.

01:19:36.450 --> 01:19:39.130
You came, you listened,
let's hear from you.

01:19:39.130 --> 01:19:40.430
And you know what
we're going to do.

01:19:40.430 --> 01:19:45.540
Because this is being taped,
I'm going to ask one of us

01:19:45.540 --> 01:19:48.170
to repeat your question.

01:19:48.170 --> 01:19:50.640
&gt;&gt; My question is this.

01:19:50.640 --> 01:19:54.500
My parents were born here,
but their parents weren't,

01:19:54.500 --> 01:19:57.930
and obviously my
great-grandparents weren't.

01:19:57.930 --> 01:20:03.010
But I remember my father
relating to us as we got older

01:20:03.010 --> 01:20:07.200
that his grandmother
lived in this country.

01:20:07.200 --> 01:20:13.410
And she had a photograph
of Mussolini in the home,

01:20:13.410 --> 01:20:15.240
and it was a real
point of contention

01:20:15.240 --> 01:20:17.400
between my father
and his grandmother.

01:20:17.400 --> 01:20:21.210
And my question is,
how common was that?

01:20:21.210 --> 01:20:25.550
How common was it
for the Italians

01:20:25.550 --> 01:20:28.630
who were here from
the old country?

01:20:28.630 --> 01:20:30.080
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto: So the
question is, how often was it

01:20:30.080 --> 01:20:34.980
that in some families you
still even today find a picture

01:20:34.980 --> 01:20:36.560
of Mussolini with
a little candle

01:20:36.560 --> 01:20:38.360
in front or a little light?

01:20:38.360 --> 01:20:39.660
Why is that?

01:20:39.660 --> 01:20:45.890
The reason is this: when
Mussolini took over, took power,

01:20:45.890 --> 01:20:52.660
he felt that Italians should
show themselves as coming

01:20:52.660 --> 01:20:57.040
from a great country
and a great race.

01:20:57.040 --> 01:21:00.190
Mussolini did a number of
very good things for Italy.

01:21:00.190 --> 01:21:04.130
For example, almost all nations
where [inaudible] was present,

01:21:04.130 --> 01:21:07.890
they would establish
Casa Italiana.

01:21:07.890 --> 01:21:11.170
It would be the cultural center
for the Italian community.

01:21:11.170 --> 01:21:14.910
It was so powerful
that in Montreal,

01:21:14.910 --> 01:21:17.940
in one of the churches,
the Madonna [inaudible],

01:21:17.940 --> 01:21:27.780
there is in the ceiling a
fresco of Mussolini on a horse

01:21:27.780 --> 01:21:29.540
with all the [inaudible].

01:21:29.540 --> 01:21:32.200
It's still there.

01:21:32.200 --> 01:21:36.330
So in a couple of the churches.

01:21:36.330 --> 01:21:39.800
So people felt that
Mussolini was helping them,

01:21:39.800 --> 01:21:43.240
supporting them, providing
them and brought back Italy.

01:21:43.240 --> 01:21:49.130
It was a period where the
mafia controlled Italy

01:21:49.130 --> 01:21:51.620
across the ocean,
came with [inaudible].

01:21:51.620 --> 01:21:55.670
So there were many
things that were

01:21:55.670 --> 01:22:02.410
to represent the Italians abroad
as coming from a great country.

01:22:02.410 --> 01:22:05.280
So people admired
Mussolini for that.

01:22:05.280 --> 01:22:10.520
And that's why especially older
generations will still keep

01:22:10.520 --> 01:22:14.430
that picture of Mussolini,
because of that period.

01:22:14.430 --> 01:22:17.450
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne:
Not only Italians

01:22:17.450 --> 01:22:21.760
or Italian Americans thought
Mussolini was good for Italy.

01:22:21.760 --> 01:22:25.930
You pointed out Roosevelt
had flattering things to say.

01:22:25.930 --> 01:22:29.970
If you look at periodicals
and newspapers from the 1920's

01:22:29.970 --> 01:22:34.540
and the early 1930's, full
of praise for bringing order,

01:22:34.540 --> 01:22:37.870
for bringing prestige and pride.

01:22:37.870 --> 01:22:41.980
One of the big turning
points in the world was

01:22:41.980 --> 01:22:47.900
when Italy invaded Ethiopia
and used poison gas.

01:22:47.900 --> 01:22:50.420
Then people began to question.

01:22:50.420 --> 01:22:55.480
But for at least 15 years, he
was considered a positive force

01:22:55.480 --> 01:22:58.550
for most of this country.

01:22:58.550 --> 01:23:00.920
A symbol, yeah.

01:23:00.920 --> 01:23:03.890
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella:
One, two, yes.

01:23:03.890 --> 01:23:06.150
You may want to also
mention your name.

01:23:06.150 --> 01:23:09.580
&gt;&gt; Yes, my name is
Mary Ann Guantano.

01:23:09.580 --> 01:23:10.880
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Excellent.

01:23:10.880 --> 01:23:20.980
&gt;&gt; My father was one of
those 55,000 prisoners of war

01:23:20.980 --> 01:23:32.240
who spent time in this
country during World War II.

01:23:32.240 --> 01:23:37.130
And my mother and
grandmother came

01:23:37.130 --> 01:23:40.850
through Ellis Island in 1920.

01:23:40.850 --> 01:23:47.780
So I'm a first-generation
American Italian,

01:23:47.780 --> 01:23:51.630
and probably a dual
citizen of Italy as well.

01:23:51.630 --> 01:23:56.780
My question though
regards the social clubs

01:23:56.780 --> 01:23:58.470
that you spoke about, Father.

01:23:58.470 --> 01:24:01.060
My sense was that
some of them came

01:24:01.060 --> 01:24:05.990
about because Italian
Americans wanted

01:24:05.990 --> 01:24:10.880
to prove their loyalty
to the United States.

01:24:10.880 --> 01:24:16.000
Or maybe that's the way
they evolved after the war.

01:24:16.000 --> 01:24:21.500
Can you speak about that at all?

01:24:21.500 --> 01:24:26.830
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Repeat
the question as best you can.

01:24:26.830 --> 01:24:31.020
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto:
Let's see, the social clubs

01:24:31.020 --> 01:24:35.490
that were formed before
and after the war.

01:24:35.490 --> 01:24:39.940
How do they react to
that transition period?

01:24:39.940 --> 01:24:43.570
When the war started, they
were looked with suspicion

01:24:43.570 --> 01:24:46.660
because they were financed
by the Fascist government.

01:24:46.660 --> 01:24:49.570
They sent money and
material for them.

01:24:49.570 --> 01:24:53.010
There is a book, Fascist
Activities in the United States.

01:24:53.010 --> 01:24:55.690
I think it was Lagumina
the author.

01:24:55.690 --> 01:24:58.330
You can find it.

01:24:58.330 --> 01:25:02.440
Just put the title Fascist
Activities in the United States,

01:25:02.440 --> 01:25:04.770
in Italian communities.

01:25:04.770 --> 01:25:09.080
So as the war started,
all those were dissolved.

01:25:09.080 --> 01:25:11.310
After the war, there
were especially groups

01:25:11.310 --> 01:25:15.150
of Italian Americans, veterans.

01:25:15.150 --> 01:25:19.390
Even here in this city
there was a very active one

01:25:19.390 --> 01:25:21.220
for a number of years.

01:25:21.220 --> 01:25:24.950
So that's how the
Italian American clubs

01:25:24.950 --> 01:25:29.440
and society started again,
with the veterans first.

01:25:29.440 --> 01:25:31.900
Then immediately after
the war, groups had formed

01:25:31.900 --> 01:25:33.200
to help Italy, rebuild Italy.

01:25:33.200 --> 01:25:37.330
So they were sending everything
from clothing to medicine

01:25:37.330 --> 01:25:39.530
to whatever was needed.

01:25:39.530 --> 01:25:42.460
So that's how everything
started again.

01:25:42.460 --> 01:25:48.270
So that's how I see it
as one of the motivations

01:25:48.270 --> 01:25:53.180
for starting again the
Italian American clubs.

01:25:53.180 --> 01:25:54.480
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella:
Okay, very good.

01:25:54.480 --> 01:25:55.780
Excellent.

01:25:55.780 --> 01:26:00.480
All right, any other comments
or questions that you may have?

01:26:00.480 --> 01:26:01.780
Yes?

01:26:01.780 --> 01:26:03.080
&gt;&gt; Will Amatruda.

01:26:03.080 --> 01:26:04.490
With regard to the sympathy
that some Italian Americans had

01:26:04.490 --> 01:26:08.560
for Mussolini before World
War II, during the time

01:26:08.560 --> 01:26:11.000
when that legislation went
through and during their time

01:26:11.000 --> 01:26:13.680
in Congress, there
was an exhibit in --

01:26:13.680 --> 01:26:16.780
I don't remember whether it
was in the capital or in one

01:26:16.780 --> 01:26:18.080
of the House and
Senate office buildings.

01:26:18.080 --> 01:26:19.380
But there was an exhibit called
[Italian name], A Secret Story.

01:26:19.380 --> 01:26:20.680
And as I was going through it,

01:26:20.680 --> 01:26:21.980
I noticed that it included a
publication of the Grand Lodge

01:26:21.980 --> 01:26:23.280
of California of the
order Sons of Italy.

01:26:23.280 --> 01:26:24.580
And it was in Italian
which I can read.

01:26:24.580 --> 01:26:25.880
And it was from 1938.

01:26:25.880 --> 01:26:27.180
And it had a reference to
Mussolini which described him

01:26:27.180 --> 01:26:28.770
as -- and I translate -- second
only to the man of Nazareth.

01:26:28.770 --> 01:26:31.050
[ Laughter ]

01:26:31.050 --> 01:26:37.090
Now as a commentary about
the idiocy of the scare

01:26:37.090 --> 01:26:42.610
about Italian American
disloyalty after Pearl Harbor,

01:26:42.610 --> 01:26:51.640
the opera singer, later the star
of South Pacific, Ezio Pinza was

01:26:51.640 --> 01:26:56.940
in the process of applying
for American citizenship.

01:26:56.940 --> 01:26:59.120
And he was within four months

01:26:59.120 --> 01:27:02.350
of the five-year
residency to get it.

01:27:02.350 --> 01:27:10.470
Well, he was interned, and the
rationale was that when he sang

01:27:10.470 --> 01:27:15.920
at the Metropolitan Opera,
he could modulate his voice

01:27:15.920 --> 01:27:19.030
to send signals to submarines.

01:27:19.030 --> 01:27:21.040
[ Laughter ]

01:27:21.040 --> 01:27:24.030
Well, since a lot of important

01:27:24.030 --> 01:27:27.400
and wealthy people were
opera fans, they went to bat

01:27:27.400 --> 01:27:31.120
for him and he was released.

01:27:31.120 --> 01:27:34.540
So it helps to have
influential friends.

01:27:34.540 --> 01:27:35.840
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto:

01:27:35.840 --> 01:27:39.180
I think your voice is loud
enough that they heard.

01:27:39.180 --> 01:27:43.870
Thank you for mentioning
that book, A Secret Story.

01:27:43.870 --> 01:27:45.450
Now it used to be an exhibit.

01:27:45.450 --> 01:27:49.130
It was published as a book,
several different books.

01:27:49.130 --> 01:27:53.690
I have here the list of
the three books published

01:27:53.690 --> 01:27:57.800
about the internment, and
you're free to take copies.

01:27:57.800 --> 01:28:01.690
The video is quite good as well
because it gives all the images.

01:28:01.690 --> 01:28:05.280
So A Secret Story started as
an exhibit that we brought

01:28:05.280 --> 01:28:09.670
to back some interest in
what was done in Congress.

01:28:09.670 --> 01:28:14.550
As one of the consequences
of that exhibit,

01:28:14.550 --> 01:28:18.550
it now has been published in a
book titled La Story Secreta.

01:28:18.550 --> 01:28:22.710
The book is branded,
a similar book.

01:28:22.710 --> 01:28:25.470
So those are the books that I
would suggest for whoever wants

01:28:25.470 --> 01:28:28.920
to get a little more
information about this period

01:28:28.920 --> 01:28:31.650
of Italian American history.

01:28:31.650 --> 01:28:32.950
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne: I should point

01:28:32.950 --> 01:28:35.840
out that there was an
anti-Mussolini press

01:28:35.840 --> 01:28:38.270
that dated back before
Mussolini.

01:28:38.270 --> 01:28:43.250
There was a very active,
vibrant left-wing communist,

01:28:43.250 --> 01:28:45.760
socialist, Italian-based press.

01:28:45.760 --> 01:28:48.880
It wasn't just against
Mussolini.

01:28:48.880 --> 01:28:51.220
It was against our
participation in World War I.

01:28:51.220 --> 01:28:54.880
It was against our
participation in World War II.

01:28:54.880 --> 01:28:58.450
And again, I told
you the stereotype

01:28:58.450 --> 01:29:03.590
of the anarchist
was very strong.

01:29:03.590 --> 01:29:09.740
And so was the presence
of these publications.

01:29:09.740 --> 01:29:13.140
During World War
II, both fascist

01:29:13.140 --> 01:29:16.490
and leftist publications were
censored in various ways.

01:29:16.490 --> 01:29:18.810
For example, they couldn't
be sent through the mail.

01:29:18.810 --> 01:29:20.720
But it wasn't uniformly that.

01:29:20.720 --> 01:29:25.680
And we have several pages
in the book on the vigor

01:29:25.680 --> 01:29:30.100
of the leftist Italian
American press.

01:29:30.100 --> 01:29:32.030
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: That
was a fascinating story

01:29:32.030 --> 01:29:37.960
about Ezio Pinza and how people
appreciating his music got him

01:29:37.960 --> 01:29:41.590
out of the possibility
of internment.

01:29:41.590 --> 01:29:44.680
&gt;&gt; One more question, please.

01:29:44.680 --> 01:29:46.690
In the mid-1800's, a lot

01:29:46.690 --> 01:29:49.180
of Irish families came
to the United States.

01:29:49.180 --> 01:29:52.070
And many of the women tried
to get jobs and they couldn't,

01:29:52.070 --> 01:29:54.280
and they ended up
being prostitutes.

01:29:54.280 --> 01:30:00.670
Did that happen with the
Italian immigration that came?

01:30:00.670 --> 01:30:02.340
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne:
Interesting question.

01:30:02.340 --> 01:30:06.590
Were Italian American women
who immigrated here forced

01:30:06.590 --> 01:30:08.180
to become prostitutes?

01:30:08.180 --> 01:30:09.620
Or was that widespread?

01:30:09.620 --> 01:30:15.610
Actually, as opposed to the
Irish, Italian American men came

01:30:15.610 --> 01:30:20.040
in much larger numbers
than the women did.

01:30:20.040 --> 01:30:25.390
And if they did come,
they were often wives

01:30:25.390 --> 01:30:28.410
and were parts of families.

01:30:28.410 --> 01:30:33.930
So I don't know of any
widespread Italian prostitution,

01:30:33.930 --> 01:30:36.580
simply because the numbers
were so overwhelmingly

01:30:36.580 --> 01:30:39.360
in favor of men coming here.

01:30:39.360 --> 01:30:41.290
Italians also went
back and forth more

01:30:41.290 --> 01:30:46.160
than other immigrant groups,
called birds of passage.

01:30:46.160 --> 01:30:49.000
They came here and went back
and forth maybe within the year,

01:30:49.000 --> 01:30:50.810
but they also came
for several years

01:30:50.810 --> 01:30:52.110
and then went back to Italy.

01:30:52.110 --> 01:30:53.820
They didn't always bring
over their families.

01:30:53.820 --> 01:30:57.140
So I don't think we need to
worry about that as a problem.

01:30:57.140 --> 01:31:00.400
But it reflects the
particular nature

01:31:00.400 --> 01:31:03.230
of Italian immigration
in the period.

01:31:03.230 --> 01:31:06.870
&gt;&gt; Father Ezio Marchetto: If
you want to get more information

01:31:06.870 --> 01:31:11.010
about that period when Irish
and then the Italians came in,

01:31:11.010 --> 01:31:13.760
read the Five Points, the book

01:31:13.760 --> 01:31:15.460
about the Five Points
in New York.

01:31:15.460 --> 01:31:18.700
And it tells you from
when it was mainly Irish

01:31:18.700 --> 01:31:22.820
to slowly Italian
to majority Italian.

01:31:22.820 --> 01:31:25.710
It will explain the
work of the children,

01:31:25.710 --> 01:31:27.530
work of women, work of men.

01:31:27.530 --> 01:31:29.140
That's a very good book.

01:31:29.140 --> 01:31:31.630
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella:
Very interesting.

01:31:31.630 --> 01:31:36.030
&gt;&gt; Linda, I'm the Italian
wannabe that Diana spoke about.

01:31:36.030 --> 01:31:38.040
[ Laughter ]

01:31:38.040 --> 01:31:41.440
But my background is German
Jewish, and my dad wrote a book

01:31:41.440 --> 01:31:45.090
on Jewish immigration
into Baltimore.

01:31:45.090 --> 01:31:48.930
And my father is not a scholar,
but he did a lot of research.

01:31:48.930 --> 01:31:51.470
And there was not a
point that you made

01:31:51.470 --> 01:31:54.220
that was not almost identical.

01:31:54.220 --> 01:31:57.810
And so you know, if you talk
about immigration, you can look

01:31:57.810 --> 01:32:00.760
at it now, same thing
that's going on.

01:32:00.760 --> 01:32:04.880
But immigration is
the large issue,

01:32:04.880 --> 01:32:07.010
not actually the nationality.

01:32:07.010 --> 01:32:11.410
And it's a longstanding
history into the United States

01:32:11.410 --> 01:32:14.990
of immigrants and the path

01:32:14.990 --> 01:32:19.050
to not only citizenship,
but to assimilation.

01:32:19.050 --> 01:32:20.350
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne: Right.

01:32:20.350 --> 01:32:23.160
You mentioned that your
family has a Jewish background

01:32:23.160 --> 01:32:26.550
and they experiences some of
the same things I talked about.

01:32:26.550 --> 01:32:29.590
And that's absolutely true.

01:32:29.590 --> 01:32:33.760
I in fact often in the
talk, I hope, said eastern

01:32:33.760 --> 01:32:35.790
and southern Europeans.

01:32:35.790 --> 01:32:39.310
For various political
reasons back home

01:32:39.310 --> 01:32:42.560
and economic reasons
back home, after 1870,

01:32:42.560 --> 01:32:44.770
a lot of southern Italians came.

01:32:44.770 --> 01:32:47.130
A lot of Jewish people came,

01:32:47.130 --> 01:32:51.390
a lot of eastern European Slavic
people came who were Christians.

01:32:51.390 --> 01:32:54.450
They were all bunched
together as undesirable

01:32:54.450 --> 01:32:57.560
for the same reasons
Italian Americas were:

01:32:57.560 --> 01:32:58.990
they didn't speak English.

01:32:58.990 --> 01:33:03.090
They were poor when they came
here, the dressed differently,

01:33:03.090 --> 01:33:05.700
they tend to live in their
own neighborhoods and so on.

01:33:05.700 --> 01:33:08.980
But yes, the whole
story involves --

01:33:08.980 --> 01:33:13.190
and I had isolated for this
group to be Italian Americans.

01:33:13.190 --> 01:33:15.680
But yes, it was.

01:33:15.680 --> 01:33:20.670
I grew up on Long Island where
lots of Italian Americans,

01:33:20.670 --> 01:33:22.570
lots of Jewish Americans,

01:33:22.570 --> 01:33:25.110
and our experiences
seem almost identical.

01:33:25.110 --> 01:33:27.860
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: It's kind
of hierarchical too, isn't it?

01:33:27.860 --> 01:33:32.850
I mean, whoever's on top doesn't
want the next one to rise.

01:33:32.850 --> 01:33:35.170
And you're always going
to have a lower spot.

01:33:35.170 --> 01:33:37.190
We could look now
in our country,

01:33:37.190 --> 01:33:40.310
those who are most
discriminated against.

01:33:40.310 --> 01:33:43.480
We had a question here, yes?

01:33:43.480 --> 01:33:44.780
&gt;&gt; Hi. Angela Fricci.

01:33:44.780 --> 01:33:47.800
So I'm thinking about the wave
of immigration on the later end,

01:33:47.800 --> 01:33:52.100
the late 1950's, early 1960's.

01:33:52.100 --> 01:33:53.530
Firstly, on my mother's side,

01:33:53.530 --> 01:33:58.020
my great-grandparents
came from Ellis Island.

01:33:58.020 --> 01:34:01.370
My father came in
the late 1950's.

01:34:01.370 --> 01:34:03.600
So I guess the question is,
thinking about that later wave

01:34:03.600 --> 01:34:06.030
of immigration, and if you
could comment on the impact

01:34:06.030 --> 01:34:10.860
of World War II on how that wave
of immigration was perceived.

01:34:11.930 --> 01:34:14.770
&gt;&gt; Linda Osborne: Not an
expert on all immigration,

01:34:14.770 --> 01:34:21.280
but how did World War II have
an impact on later immigration?

01:34:21.280 --> 01:34:23.240
As I mentioned, in 1952,

01:34:23.240 --> 01:34:28.400
there was another immigration
law passed, the McCarron law.

01:34:28.400 --> 01:34:32.830
And it did not take
away national quotas.

01:34:32.830 --> 01:34:35.810
So it talked about trying
to reunite families here.

01:34:35.810 --> 01:34:37.110
No, no, sorry.

01:34:37.110 --> 01:34:39.870
It did not take away the quotas.

01:34:39.870 --> 01:34:41.230
They still remained low.

01:34:41.230 --> 01:34:44.870
People found ways to come
here outside the quota system.

01:34:44.870 --> 01:34:49.860
We began to take refugees,
although actually unfortunately,

01:34:49.860 --> 01:34:52.280
very few after World War II.

01:34:52.280 --> 01:34:58.010
But those would mostly
have been Jewish refugees.

01:34:58.010 --> 01:35:02.720
I don't think the same
psychological obstacles were

01:35:02.720 --> 01:35:05.890
there towards people coming.

01:35:05.890 --> 01:35:10.640
But the rules were
there until 1965.

01:35:10.640 --> 01:35:16.280
And that's when they
abandoned the quota system.

01:35:16.280 --> 01:35:18.400
And I know people who
came in that period,

01:35:18.400 --> 01:35:22.060
too often they were -- for
one thing they were often not

01:35:22.060 --> 01:35:25.630
poverty-stricken from the
19th century with no hope.

01:35:25.630 --> 01:35:29.380
In Italy they were
educated, they were skilled.

01:35:29.380 --> 01:35:32.870
And they could fly here.

01:35:32.870 --> 01:35:34.550
It was just a very,

01:35:34.550 --> 01:35:37.250
very different group
of people applying.

01:35:37.250 --> 01:35:40.800
But in terms of the numbers,
the actual numbers, I'm not sure

01:35:40.800 --> 01:35:44.800
that there was an enormous
difference until after '65.

01:35:44.800 --> 01:35:47.360
I'm not sure though.

01:35:47.360 --> 01:35:48.660
Good question.

01:35:48.660 --> 01:35:52.860
&gt;&gt; Constance Morella: Do we have
any other comments or questions?

01:35:52.860 --> 01:35:56.510
How about a comment about
how great the panel was?

01:35:56.510 --> 01:35:59.050
[ Applause ]

